<TEXT>
a freighter carrying petroleum coke collided 
with a tugboat sunday off delaware damaging both vessels and 
injuring two people the coast guard said 
authorities said there was no indication any of the coke spilled 
into the atlantic ocean 
the 593foot freighter doo yang leader and the 113foot tug 
socrates collided around 630 pm 35 miles due east of cape 
henlopen in southern delaware coast guard spokesman breck smith 
said in philadelphia 
the freighter stopped because it had a ruptured tank believed to 
be leaking engine fuel said coast guard petty officer richard 
minnich 
when they noticed the leak they transfered that fuel back to 
another tank minnich said 
theres a onemeter hole on the starboard side the hole is 
above the waterline said james graham a spokesman for the coast 
guardss 5th district headquarters in portsmouth va 
the ship was carrying petroleum coke a residue from a process 
that breaks down petroleum products the freighter is owned by doo 
yang shipping lines in south korea 
investigators from the coast guards marine safety office in 
philadelphia were dispatched to the collision site 
graham said the coast guard cutter point franklin with 
emergency medical technicians aboard was in the area and was en 
route to the tug to assist one of the injured but said the injury 
didnt appear to be lifethreatening 
he said authorities believe the other man had a back injury and 
did not require major medical attention 
the tug was towing a 300foot barge of sugar from west palm 
beach fla to yonkers ny just north of new york city 
the tug is owned by allied towing corp of norfolk va minnich 
said 
minnich said the tug received damage to its cabin but was able 
to continue on its route and was being accompanied by another tug 
owned by the same company 
neither ship lost any of its cargo graham said 
</TEXT>
