<DOCNO> AP900122-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a sign on a freeway here reads 
little saigon marking an enclave that is home to many of the 
250000 vietnamese settled in southern california 
now the region is receiving the first wave of 100000 political 
prisoners allowed to leave vietnam and experts are calling on 
vietnameseamericans to help the refugees survive and thrive in 
america as government funding dwindles 
my argument to them is look youve been helped by the 
american government the american people and others said loc 
nguyen director of the refugee resettlement program for the 
catholic charities of los angeles 
you keep pushing the government to allow more refugees and 
say we need more help i say they are our people we have to 
take care of them said nguyen 
the refugees themselves are cautioned about economic realities 
we explain to them that real life in the united states does 
not look like on television said rev bao xuan nguyen of the 
saigon christian reformed church in westminster i ask them come 
back with a realistic view if they want to build their own 
life everything must start at the beginning 
the vietnamese community in los angeles is estimated at 150000 
and at up to 100000 in adjacent orange county officials say the 
largest concentration outside vietnam 
about 7000 prisoners of communist vietnams reeducation 
camps some of whom spent more than a decade imprisoned after the 
wars end are expected to be resettled by september 
of the total 100000 or so eligible to emigrate to the united 
states in the next five years most are expected to settle in 
southern california said william gayk demographer for orange 
county 
texas florida and washington dc also have large vietnamese 
populations gayk said 
the amount of federal money available for an individuals 
resettlement in 1983 was 12000 according to dianne edwards 
director of adult and employment services for the orange county 
social services agency in 1989 it was less than 4000 she said 
there are government programs in place to help such refugees as 
the former political prisoners she said including cash 
assistance medical aid and language and job training 
we are not anticipating a major drain on county resources as a 
result of the former pows she said the issue we are seeking 
to address is that refugee funding has gone down considerably in 
the last 10 years 
leaders in the vietnamese community say the decline in funding 
presents an opportunity to unite in support of their newly arriving 
countrymen 
the local and federal government has been doing a lot of work 
to resettle the refugees we feel we should do our part said 
tony lam a businessman who has been active in refugee resettlement 
in orange county since his arrival 15 years ago 
the rev nguyen is working to enlist even recent refugees in the 
cause 
i say you wanted me to sponsor you how about when you have 
a stable life you sponsor others nguyen tells his 
parishioners do for them what people did for you 
those involved in resettlement agree that a number of the former 
prisoners many of whom were military officers who fought for 
south vietnam against the communists and politicians are arriving 
with advantages their predecessors lacked 
this group is the easiest to work with said loc nguyen of 
catholic charities which handles up to 40 percent of the total 
vietnamese refugee caseload in los angeles and works under an 
agreement with the state department as do a dozen other volunteer 
agencies 
they have an aboveaverage education and often are 
collegeeducated their english is much better than other groups 
they may have been government or military officials or been 
associated with us firms he said 
loc nguyen and others said the refugees need help adjusting to a 
lower standard of living than they might have expected here and 
the limits of public assistance 
that might mean a man who was an engineer or highranking 
military officer in vietnam will have to start out here as a 
minimumwage assembly line worker he said 
loc nguyen said he encourages refugees to take such jobs while 
educating themselves for more skilled positions so they can stay 
off welfare 
i tell them with welfare you lose your confidence you lose 
your energy you become merely a welfare receiver who waits for the 
check he said 
</TEXT>
