<TEXT>
vice president dan quayle facing a possible 
chilly reception in latin america as he offers to explain the us 
invasion of panama would not be the first presidential emissary to 
run into trouble in the region 
such esteemed former latin america travelers as nelson 
rockefeller richard nixon and rosalynn carter were sent by 
presidents on goodwill trips and all encountered stormy receptions 
in some cases violence 
quayle leaves saturday on a mission to try to quell the 
resentment left in central and south america by president bushs 
dec 20 military invasion of panama 
none of the countries in the region has officially rebuffed 
quayle but some officials have let it be known his visit would be 
less than welcome so soon after the invasion many are upset that 
us invasion troops remain in panama 
instead of receiving quayle at home some leaders plan to meet 
with him at three presidential inaugurations on saturday in 
honduras and in chile and brazil in midmarch 
quayle himself acknowledged theres a matter of timing 
involving diplomatic sensitivities over when he should go 
past efforts by washington to be chummy with latin america have 
encountered problems stemming from a variety of sources including 
latin resentment over the historical us pattern of manipulating 
the regions internal political and economic affairs 
the most volatile trips in recent history were that of vice 
president richard nixon in 1958 and a series of trips by new york 
gov nelson rockefeller in 1969 
in contrast to those times when most of the region was under 
dictatorship and military rule quayle will visit a region that has 
turned overwhelmingly to democratic government 
on an 18day goodwill mission for president eisenhower nixon 
was the target of violent antius demonstrations in peru and 
venezuela and lesser outbursts and heckling by university students 
in argentina uruguay paraguay and colombia 
rockthrowing mobs confronted nixon in lima and caracas rioters 
shattered the windows of his limousine in caracas and tried to drag 
him and his wife from the car before their motorcade managed to 
escape 
eisenhower ordered us military troops to stand by in puerto 
rico and the guantanamo bay base in cuba in case nixon needed 
protection 
in lima shouting demonstrators threw rocks and fruit at his 
speakers platform in bogota police broke up several antinixon 
demonstrations 
when nixon became president he dispatched rockefeller to help 
formulate a new policy toward latin america 
voicing sentiments much like those stated by bush in the first 
year of his presidency nixon talked about the regions importance 
and us hopes for cooperative ties with its hemispheric neighbors 
but rockefellers mission was marked at nearly every stop by 
violence riots bombings gunfights or terrorism eight people 
were killed in incidents directly or indirectly connected to the 
visit 
the first trouble signs came in guatemala where newspapers 
blasted his visit as useless and in el salvador where placards 
read rockefeller go home 
in nicaragua students burned a us flag peru then canceled 
rockefellers trip to lima annoyed that the united states had 
suspended arms sales to peru following seizures of us fishing 
boats 
following violence in ecuador colombia and honduras word came 
that venezuela and chile wanted to be stricken from rockefellers 
itinerary 
in montevideo uruguay rampaging students protesting both 
rockefellers visit and their governments economic austerity 
program smashed car windows and threw firebombs 
after returning home rockefeller submitted to nixon 83 
recommendations on how to improve hemispheric cooperation and help 
solve the regions social political and economic problems 
all but a few were ignored 
when rosalynn carter toured seven nations as her husbands 
emissary on a 13day trip in 1977 the dissension was mostly less 
overt 
but students in quito ecuador threw stones and bricks and 
shouted antiamerican slogans near where she met with government 
officials the noise at times nearly drowned out her voice in the 
legislative palace 
elsewhere on her tour there were private diplomatic rumblings 
complaining that carter had sent his wife rather than a 
highranking official who would have more appropriate stature to 
conduct diplomatic talks 
in brazil mrs carter trod on delicate ground by raising the 
carter administrations unhappiness with the military governments 
human rights record and ruffled feathers by announcing she would 
meet there with two american churchmen who had reportedly been 
beaten by police 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

