<TEXT>
when amber yarger arrived at school 
recently she had to sit in the back of her classroom and couldnt 
play with her browneyed friends at recess 
she and the other blueeyed third graders had to drink from a 
fountain with warm water use a restroom without paper towels and 
stand in the back of lines 
it was part of a firsthand lesson in discrimination devised by 
faculty at driscoll elementary school to teach 60 thirdgraders the 
meaning of discrimination as part of the celebration of martin 
luther king jrs birthday 
i had this one friend who had blue eyes and she started 
crying because she didnt know what was happening amber said 
sunday 
blueeyed children were snubbed one day in the program that 
began jan 9 those with brown eyes and those with hazel and green 
eyes were discriminated against on subsequent days 
some children were upset at their separation from friends and 
classmates for a day teacher cathy pedersen said but she hopes 
they learned the lesson 
the goal really was to get them to understand just how unfair 
prejudice is i wanted them to say this is unfair i cant 
help the way i was born if they can grow up without prejudice 
they can carry that on with their children she said 
</TEXT>
