<TEXT>
in languages from west african pidgin english 
to the tagalog of the philippines popular music financed by the 
us government aims at discouraging young people from having sex 
critics have long complained that many pop songs promote sex 
but the songs commissioned by the us agency for international 
development seek to do the reverse 
wait for me the title song of a bestselling album in 
nigeria last year says in pidgin english 
dis tin them call love 
na serious affair 
make you think well 
before you gree 
translation this thing they call love is a serious affair 
think well before you agree 
the song was recorded by king sunny ade known in west africa 
for a style called juju and onyeku onwenu he has three wives and 
12 children she is a graduate of wellesley college who tried 
journalism before turning to the stage the agency said she wrote 
both music and lyrics in pidgin and traditional english 
another song choices presents an alternative policy 
yes we shouldnt make children 
we cannot take care of 
there are ways of making love 
without making children 
many people who work to raise the living standards of poor 
countries see the rapid growth of their population as the chief 
obstacle 
growth rates in developing countries will remain high for 
several decades even if couples have fewer children said a study 
by the world bank the chief source of aid for the third world 
absolute annual increases will be close to 80 million 
people a year well into the next century 
the us agencys population program also provides donations of 
contraceptives including 69 billion condoms over the past two 
decades 
the nigerian albums popularity has spilled over into 
neighboring countries the next step will be another record for 
nearby frenchspeaking republics like zaire senegal and the ivory 
coast the agency says 
the agency said it was too early to say what effect the african 
music has had but a study will be made later 
two songs recorded earlier for latin america were the subject of 
an analysis by the population communication service of johns 
hopkins university the idea for the project came from a conference 
of the service in 1983 
with the government agencys support it blossomed into two 
musical videos television commercials radio spots records and 
jackets posters and press materials the songs were recorded by 
tatiana palacios of mexico and johnny lozada correa of puerto rico 
the agency said the songs topped the charts in mexico and peru 
and reached the top 10 in nine other countries 
we made an investment of about 350000 and got about 5 
million worth of free air time said duff gillespie the agencys 
director for population 
the universitys study said that although no data were 
collected attitudes about delaying sexual relations may have been 
strengthened especially among young women in mexico 
one of the most important conclusions from this evaluation is 
that popular songs and the broadcast media can be successfully 
employed to reach young people with a positive social message about 
sexual responsibility even if the message contradicts the theme of 
the majority of competing popular songs it added 
in the philippines one song was called i still believe and 
lea salonga sang in english 
i dont think its right to need me 
just for a lonely night 
to which according to the agency charlie masso replied in 
tagalog 
im willing to wait for a while 
the song was number one in the philippine charts for two months 
the agency said 
