congress returns to washington this week for a 
1990 session preoccupied with two issues that have taken on an 
unusual linkage the federal budget deficit and the starkly 
changing face of eastern europe 
lawmakers will be caught between a desire to reward countries 
emerging from more than four decades of soviet domination and the 
need to shrink spending in an unyielding budget that already is 
being asked to make room for improving programs at home 
the year will be consumed with this discussion of how the 
united states deals with a host of new relationships with poland 
hungary east germany romania bulgaria and czechoslovakia said 
sen richard lugar rind a senior member of the senate foreign 
relations committee 
