<TEXT>
career diplomats got twothirds of the 
ambassadorships during president bushs first year and are likely 
to receive almost all the embassy openings for the rest of his 
term the white house personnel director says 
charles g untermeyer said sunday that despite criticism from 
democrats about ambassadorships being awarded as plums to the 
republican partys biggest benefactors bush has achieved his goal 
of putting diplomatic newcomers in no more than onethird of the 
us embassies 
from now on close to 100 percent of ambassadorial 
appointments will go to career foreign service officers untermeyer 
said in an interview 
henceforth for the rest of the first bush term i expect 
very very few noncareer nominations he said 
by untermeyers count 97 of the 145 ambassadorships have gone 
to career diplomats or 67 percent ninetythree are already in 
place one is awaiting senate confirmation and three are still 
getting cleared before they are formally nominated 
fortyeight ambassadorships have gone or will go to noncareer 
people 42 have been confirmed two are awaiting senate 
confirmation and four are in the white house clearance process one 
of bushs appointees ruth washington the ambassador to gambia 
was killed saturday in an auto accident in new york state 
untermeyer said that 10 or fewer of the noncareer envoys were 
what you could call major donors including several who made the 
gops team 100 by giving 100000 or more to the party for the 
1988 election battle they included real estate developers melvin 
sembler now ambassador to australia and joseph zappala now envoy 
to spain 
many of the noncareer people are there for past proven 
loyalty to george bush said untermeyer but their ranks include 
such relatively poor people as evelyn teegan a former 
republican national committeewoman from minnesota who is now 
ambassador to fiji and sally novetzke a party activist and 
longtime bush loyalist from iowa who is ambassador to malta 
sen paul s sarbanes dmd objected to several of bushs 
politically connected nominees last year and managed to block joy 
silvermans nomination to be ambassador to barbados she gave 
180000 to republican causes before the last election 
untermeyer said the white house has not yet decided whether to 
resubmit her nomination 
the percentage of noncareer envoys is down from roughly 40 
percent at the end of the reagan administration said untermeyer 
the 33 percent goal was achieved recently when bush nominated a 
career diplomat edward rowell to be ambassador to luxembourg 
long a post reserved for presidential pals 
originally bush nominated his chief campaign fundraiser 
frederick bush no relation to the luxembourg post but the 
senate batted that nomination back in august after frederick bush 
came under scrutiny for contracts he received from the reagan 
administrations scandalridden department of housing and urban 
development 
theodore s wilkinson president of the foreign service 
association which represents foreign service officers said the 
noncareer appointments have been very uneven theres some very 
good ones and some very inexperienced ones 
by law wilkinson said even the noncareer appointees are 
supposed to be knowledgeable about the history economics politics 
and language of the country they are assigned to some dont seem 
to meet those criteria said wilkinson 
with congress returning from a twomonth recess untermeyer said 
the white house will send up 30 nominations on tuesday 
some democrats accused bush last year of running a swiss 
cheese government and taking too long to fill vacancies 
but untermeyer said only 5 percent of the 659 top jobs in 
cabinet departments and independent agencies now are vacant 
untermeyer said 327 bush nominees have been confirmed or 
appointed 142 jobs were filled by reagan holdovers 42 are 
awaiting senate confirmation 113 are in the white house clearance 
process and 35 are vacant 
