minus nine 
the union which claims 70000 supporters has presented the 
first open organized opposition to a government ruled by the 
communist party since 1921 longer than any other country outside 
mongolias patron state the soviet union 
the reform group organized two small demonstrations in december 
and another on jan 14 that drew about 5000 it had official 
permission for all three of those gatherings 
so far both sides appear to be trying to avoid a confrontation 
although the governments ban and the groups latest protest 
suggests they are hardening their positions 
at sundays demonstration people carried banners reading if 
people are rich the mongolian nation will be rich and calling 
for an end to special privileges for officials 
one banner written in english read we support perestroika and 
glasnost a reference to soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs 
programs of reform and openness 
another group calling itself the democratic socialist movement 
and saying it was more radical than the democratic union passed out 
fliers calling for a free press a multiparty system adherence to 
the un declaration on human rights more independence in the 
economic sphere and greater protection of the national culture 
mongolias economy and culture have long been dominated by the 
soviet union the russian cyrillic alphabet was officially adopted 
in 1946 the traditional mongolian script was banned until about 
five years ago 
many of mongolias 2 million people dispersed across grasslands 
roughly the size of western europe still have deep links to their 
herdsman traditions and the nations small amount of industry 
sprang largely from soviet or east european aid 
the leader of the democratic union 27yearold sanjaasuren 
zorig speaking at a news conference after the rally did not rule 
out confrontation with the government however he said his group 
puts great hopes on the sober minds of government leaders 
according to the western source 
zorig said his group regards itself as a guarantor for 
developing and deepening democracy in mongolia and said it stands 
for a multiparty system 
he blamed mongolias low level of economic development on 
central controls over the economy and state ownership of property 
</TEXT>
