<TEXT>
the abortive debut of a cigarette aimed 
primarily at blacks suggests that there are new limits to tobacco 
marketing 
r j reynolds co the countrys secondlargest tobacco 
company announced friday that it was canceling plans to use 
philadelphia as a test market for uptown a lowmenthol cigarette 
designed to lure black smokers the plans had so enraged 
philadelphia leaders they organized a grassroots opposition 
movement that attracted the attention of the bush administration 
although reynolds officials say they havent given up on uptown 
they concede that theyll have to find another way to market the 
brand if they decide to keep it and other tobacco companies may 
face new criticism over their old strategy of marketing to women 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan who was 
among the strongest critics of uptown said last week that he also 
plans to attack cigarette companies that target women 
we should be doing things to improve the health of our 
citizens not impairing the health he said so that when a 
tobacco company profits from this indeed the rest of society our 
insurance companies our hospitals our companies also hurt 
charyn sutton marketing consultant for the american lung 
association noted that lung cancer recently became the no 1 
cancer in women 
the possibility of a rise in lung cancer among blacks is a 
very scary scary prospect and especially when you look at a 
community already overburdened with smokingrelated diseases 
sutton said if you give black people a cigarette of their own 
death rates will go into the stratosphere 
black men have a 58 percent higher incidence of lung cancer than 
white men according to the us public health service and 
compared with whites blacks lose twice as many years of life 
because of smokingrelated diseases 
