scientists made final inspections of a threestage 
rocket today as japan prepared to become the third nation to send a 
spacecraft to the moon 
our staffs have almost finished the final check of electrical 
systems of the spacecraft so far everythings perfect said 
tadashige takiya a spokesman for the institute of space and 
astronautical science in kagoshima in southern japan 
if tuesdays flight is successful japans musesa would be the 
first spacecraft to visit the moon since the soviet union landed 
the unmanned vehicle luna 24 on its surface in 1976 the united 
states is the only other nation that has sent spacecraft to the 
moon 
the launch is scheduled at 848 pm 648 am est tuesday 
from the kagoshima space center takiya said 
the plan is to send the musesa into a highly elliptical earth 
orbit that will bring it about 10000 miles from the moon on march 
18 
japanese space centers are incapable of tracing the flight all 
the way so centers in canberra australia and at california 
institute of technology will help takiya said 
the craft is to release a smaller satellite just before crossing 
the moons orbit a kick motor aboard the smaller craft will 
propel it into a lunar orbit the institute said 
the smaller satellite is to send data to the mother satellite on 
space temperatures and electric fields while the mother satellite 
continues circling earth swinging by the moon and collecting data 
on space dust and other phenomena 
the governmentfunded flight will be the 13th satellite launched 
by japan and the fifth use of the m3s2 rocket 
the japanese rocket an m3s2 made by nissan motor co is a 
threestage solidfuel rocket that weighs 62 tons 
japans rocket program has shown a high success rate but last 
august the national space development agency had its first failure 
in 20 launchings when the first stage of an h1 rocket failed to 
ignite 
