a bibb county ga school bond referendum 
attacked by blacks as a violation of the federal voting rights act 
was legal the supreme court ruled today 
the court without waiting to hear arguments in the case upheld 
a ruling that permitted the countys voters to approve 29 million 
to aircondition existing schools and build a new high school 
the justices decision was not accompanied by any written 
opinion there was no recorded dissenting vote 
blacks in the county who favored the air conditioning but 
opposed the new school said permitting both proposals to be voted 
on together was racially biased they said the proposed school in a 
predominantly white area would require busing black students to 
attend classes there 
the blacks sought under the voting rights act of 1965 to have 
the us attorney general review the referendum proposal before it 
was placed on the ballot a process called preclearance 
but a special threejudge federal court ruled last year that the 
school boards decision to link the air conditioning and a new 
school in a single bond issue is not the kind of voting change 
requiring preclearance 
the threejudge court acknowledged that the supreme court has 
upheld preclearance for setting election dates changing candidate 
qualifications and altering voting procedures 
but the panel agreeing with legal arguments submitted by the 
justice department said defining the scope of a bond issue 
proposal is a routine matter for the school board to decide 
those who challenged the referendum format said the method 
the board chose submerged the political will of bibb countys black 
voters voters favoring all or none of the bond issues were able to 
cast a fully effective ballot those voters who were divided on the 
issues were not 
the challengers said there was racially polarized voting over 
the bond issue and that the school board scheduled the election to 
reduce the chances of a proportionally larger turnout by blacks 
over whites 
they said the school board rescinded a plan to submit the bond 
issue to voters on march 8 1988 socalled super tuesday in last 
years presidential primaries when the civil rights leader jesse 
jackson was on the georgia ballot 
on that date 11375 blacks and 23706 whites in bibb county 
voted when the bond issue was approved on election day nov 8 
1988 14731 blacks and 35153 whites voted 
the bond issue passed 21915 votes to 21287 
asked for its views in the case the bush administration urged 
the high court to uphold the threejudge courts ruling 
the case is lucas vs townsend 89400 
