the supreme court today agreed to use a 
decadelong dispute over the rights of haitian refugees to decide 
when the government must pay legal fees to people who sue it 
successfully 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal aimed 
at limiting such fees 
the refugees sued the government in 1981 over its policy of 
locking up aliens caught while trying to enter the united states 
illegally 
until 1981 the government generally released aliens on 
parole pending hearings on their applications for official 
admission to the country 
the haitians said they almost never were paroled before their 
applications were acted upon a process that can take longer than a 
year 
the refugees accused the government of discriminating against 
them because they are black and also contended that the 
immigration and naturalization service violated federal rules by 
summarily adopting harsher treatment for haitians than other aliens 
the refugees ultimately won an important though not total 
victory 
they did not win on the discrimination claim but the government 
conceded that the ins may not consider race or national origin in 
determining parole new rules were adopted for handling refugees 
federal courts that reviewed the case said there is no doubt the 
haitians won their freedom because of the lawsuit those refugees 
later returned to custody were detained under new fairer rules 
the lower courts said 
the government has argued that the haitians did not win key 
elements of their lawsuit and should not be entitled to recover 
legal fees under the equal access to justice act 
the act generally requires reimbursement of legal fees for those 
who prevail in suits against the government 
a federal judge ruled against the government on the fees 
question awarding more than 1 million to the lawyers who 
represented the haitians 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals last year substantially 
upheld the judges decision while ordering further hearings to 
recompute the amount owed the lawyers 
the appeals court also said the government must reimburse the 
haitians lawyers for fees they incurred litigating the fees issue 
in the first place what the appeals court called the fees for 
fees issue 
we hold that the united states may not oppose a fees for 
fees request solely on the ground that its position in the fee 
litigation was substantially justified the 11th circuit court 
said 
that issue prompted the bush administrations appeal to the 
supreme court acted on today 
justice department lawyers said the 11th circuit court ruling 
conflicts with decisions by other federal appeals courts 
the case is commissioner of ins vs jean 89601 
