the supreme court today refused to require 
arbitration for hundreds of thousands of federal workers when they 
are fired demoted or otherwise disciplined 
the court without comment rejected appeals by a labor union 
and the federal labor relations authority seeking broader job 
protection for federal employees 
at issue were the rights of as many as 450000 employees known 
as excepted workers because they hold their jobs without having 
to take civil service tests 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled last may that the 
civil service reform act of 1978 does not require government 
agencies to bargain over creation of grievance arbitration 
procedure for the excepted workers 
congress carefully constructed a scheme that would ensure 
uniformity in personnel decisions and promote efficiency of 
administration the appeals court said requiring arbitration for 
excepted workers would undermine the structure of the law that 
court said 
the may ruling was a defeat for the national treasury employees 
union which sought to extend arbitration protection to employees 
in the chief counsels office of the internal revenue service 
the bush administration supported the appeals court ruling but 
justice department lawyers noted that congress is considering 
amending civil service law to expand job protection for excepted 
employees 
the cases are national treasury employees union vs treasury 
department 89610 and federal labor relations authority vs 
treasury department 89758 
