the supreme court today refused to revive a 
federal civil rights lawsuit by five people prosecuted for 
antiabortion picketing outside a san diego medical clinic 
the justices without comment let stand a decision dismissing 
allegations that the clinics operators violated the pickets 
freespeech rights 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals last june 23 threw out 
11800 awards each of the five pickets had won in a federal trial 
james collins jr tammy lee collins kimberlee huckaby joan 
patton and cheryl sullenger sued over an oct 1 1985 incident at 
the womencare clinic 
on that day a group of protesters demonstrated across the 
street from the clinic some of them were subject to a state court 
injunction issued about a year earlier that barred them from 
demonstrating or picketing any closer than across the street 
from the clinics property 
the five people involved in this case picketed on the public 
sidewalk on womencares side of the street 
two clinic employees summoned police who after talking with the 
pickets decided to take no action but san diego police sgt 
thomas packer told the clinic employees they could make citizens 
arrests under california law charging the pickets with violating 
the 1984 injunction 
the two employees accompanied by police officers placed the 
five pickets under arrest police detained the group long enough to 
issue misdemeanor citations for violating the injunction 
the five pickets were not subject to the 1984 injunction and 
the charges were dropped prior to trial they subsequently sued in 
federal court the clinics owners and the two employees who 
arrested them 
the suit involving a muchused civil rights law alleged false 
arrest and freespeech violations 
a jury ruled for the pickets but the 9th circuit court threw 
out the jurys award 
the appeals court said the arrests made by the two clinic 
employees did not amount to action taken under the color of state 
law and therefore could not be the basis for the civil rights 
suit 
the appeals court sent back the falsearrest claim for a retrial 
the case is collins vs womancare 89819 
