<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to settle a 
dispute over how much money pleasure boat owners may be required to 
pay for damages in some boating accidents 
the court said it will hear an appeal by the owner of a yacht 
destroyed in a fire while docked at a lake michigan marina in 
indiana 
the accident occurred sept 24 1985 when a fire broke out 
aboard everett sissons 56foot yacht the ultorian it caused 
extensive damage to the washington park marina in michigan city 
ind and other boats docked there 
the fire was believed to have been caused by a defective washer 
and dryer aboard the yacht 
the owners of the marina and the other damaged boats sued for 
more than 275000 
sisson whose boat was valued at about 600000 before the fire 
said he should be required to pay the others no more than 800 
the ultorians value after the fire 
his arguments for restricting the damages were based on maritime 
and admiralty laws that protect ship owners from having to pay big 
court awards in lawsuits 
but the 7th us circuit court of appeals ruled last year that 
the liability limits do not apply when the accident is caused by a 
pleasure boat moored at a recreational marina 
the appeals court said the liability limits only apply to 
cases directly involving commercial maritime activity or to cases 
involving exclusively noncommercial activities in which the wrong 
has a potentially disruptive impact on martime commerce and 
involves navigation 
the appeals court based its ruling in part on a 1982 supreme 
court ruling in a case in which two pleasure boats collided 
this may be too narrow and mechanical an interpretation of the 
supreme court decision the appeals court said but the 
specific language of the court seems to support it if the ultorian 
had been under way in the shipping channel when the fire broke out 
we might reach a different result 
bush administration lawyers urged that sissons appeal be 
granted and his case be used to clear up uncertainty over the issue 
the 1982 decision provides modest guidance with respect to 
cases that do not involve navigation or commercial shipping 
justice department lawyers said 
the case is sisson vs ruby 882041 
</TEXT>
