<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let public 
employee labor unions get from the government the home addresses of 
federal workers 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that the 
workers privacy would be violated if government agencies are 
forced to divulge the information to the unions 
the federal labor relations authority in a series of decisions 
said unions are entitled to the names and addresses of the workers 
they represent in collective bargaining 
the authority said withholding the information is an unfair 
labor practice noting that labor law requires private employers to 
give unions the addresses of workers they represent 
there is little privacy right in keeping ones home address a 
secret from the union since the recipient of union mail is free to 
throw it away unopened the labor authority said 
disclosing the addresses will contribute to the unions 
ability to communicate effectively with its bargaining unit 
employees added the authority which handles disputes between 
government employee unions and their employers 
the us circuit court of appeals here overturned the labor 
authoritys ruling last september saying workers privacy rights 
outweigh the unions need for the information particularly since 
there are other ways for the unions to communicate with employees 
in the appeals acted on today the unions said they should be 
allowed to communicate with members in the privacy of the workers 
homes and be allowed to recruit new members by mail 
in ruling against the unions the appeals court relied in part 
on a 1989 supreme court decision that said the fbi is not required 
by the freedom of information act to reveal rap sheets 
containing arrest and conviction records of millions of americans 
federal employees have privacy interests in their names and 
home addresses that must be protected and the relevant public 
interest in disclosure though not nothing is outweighed the 
appeals court said 
bush administration lawyers asked the justices not to disturb 
the appeals courts ruling 
in a related case last year the high court ordered the st 
louisbased 8th us circuit court of appeals to study the issue 
further 
the cases are american federation of government employees vs 
department of health and human services 89444 national treasury 
employees union vs treasury department 89566 and federal labor 
relations authority vs treasury department 89853 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

