<TEXT>
a california church that won a major supreme 
court propertyrights case in 1987 today lost a followup bid to be 
compensated for losing the use of its land 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that los 
angeles county officials are not required to pay the church for any 
losses it suffered 
the church first english evangelical lutheran in glendale 
calif operated a camp called lutherglen on 21 acres of land in 
the mountains north of los angeles 
forest fires in the summer of 1977 burned off much of the 
vegetation there and flooding from heavy rains the next year 
leveled the camps buildings 
floods in the area also killed 10 people swept away bridges and 
other buildings and inflicted million of dollars in damages 
los angeles county enacted an interim ordinance that barred 
reconstruction of the lutherglen buildings while officials looked 
for a permanent solution to the flooding threat 
the supreme court in 1987 used the case to rule that landowners 
can be awarded compensation when government regulations bar them 
from using their property 
but the justices sent the churchs case back to a california 
appeals court to decide whether the church would receive any money 
the state appeals court ruled in may 1969 that the church is not 
entitled to be paid because it was not deprived of all use of its 
property even temporarily and because whatever uses were denied 
were justified by public safety concerns 
the appeals court said lutherglen still could be used for 
various camping and recreational activities 
moreover the state court said the county was justified in 
preventing rebuilding because of the threat to life and property 
from another flood 
what first english can no longer do is rebuild the bunkhouses 
and similar permanent living structures which might house the 
potential victims of a future flood the state court said 
these zoning restrictions represent a valid exercise of the 
police power and not an unconstitutional taking of property 
without compensation 
the church said the state court ruling amounts to willful 
defiance of the supreme courts 1987 ruling 
the california courts do not yet appear to have received the 
message that they are depriving property owners of their rights 
the church said 
the national association of realtors the national association 
of home builders and the conservative pacific legal foundation 
supported the churchs appeal 
the california attorney generals office urged the justices to 
leave the state court ruling intact 
the case is first english church vs los angeles county 89826 
</TEXT>
