the supreme court today refused to reinstate a 
350000 award a massachusetts hospital was ordered to pay the 
family of a girl who lost sight in her right eye after surgery 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that reduced the 
medical malpractice judgment to 20000 under a state law that 
protects charitable institutions 
new england medical center in boston was sued in 1983 by joseph 
and elizabeth english their daughter kerrie ann underwent 
cataract surgery at the hospital in 1980 at age 8 she developed an 
infection after the operation 
a jury awarded the family 350000 against the hospital but 
returned verdicts in favor of two doctors who treated the girl 
a judge reduced the damages to 20000 under a 1971 
massachusetts law that imposes that cap for personal injury 
lawsuits against charities 
the massachusetts supreme judicial court upheld the reduced 
damages last year 
we are not without misgivings about the paltriness of the 
20000 cap but we cannot correctly declare the statute to be 
unconstitutional the state court said a change in the amount 
of the cap may be appropriate but that is a legislative decision 
lawyers for the english family said the law violates 
constitutional equal protection guarantees only victims of 
injuries caused by charities are subject to the discriminatory cap 
they said 
the statute must be seen as the product of a powerful lobby 
securing unneeded protection from the legislature at the expense of 
an unrepresented and powerless class of victims the lawyers said 
the statute fails to make a distinction between victims to 
whom 20000 would be a boon and those to whom it would barely be a 
beginning the appeal said 
the case is english vs new england medical center 89825 
