<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let new 
mexico officials break part of a 1980 pact they say put the states 
four prisons under daytoday federal court control 
the court without comment let stand rulings that upheld the 
10yearold court consent decree 
the dispute dates back to a 1977 lawsuit by inmates of the 
states penitentiary at the time new mexicos only prison the 
suit challenged prison conditions and practices as unconstitutional 
a partial settlement was agreed to in 1979 a broader agreement 
between prison authorities and inmates was reached several months 
after 33 inmates were killed a february 1980 riot at the 
penitentiary 
the 1980 courtapproved pact which covered all future prisons 
and inmates as well set standards for numerous aspects of prison 
life 
some of the standards such as those governing food services and 
medical care were not challenged by state officials 
but others were attacked in a 1987 request seeking to modify the 
1980 agreement 
specifically state officials objected to these requirements 
inmate security classifications must be made by a threemember 
committee representing a prisons psychological program and 
security staffs with participation by the individual inmate 
maximum security may be used only for inmates who have 
committed or been linked to particular acts involving prison 
security 
the states appeal said the requirement makes maximum security 
unavailable for known gang leaders who have not themselves 
engaged in recent misconduct 
inmates may be punished only for certain designated offenses 
and only for specified lengths of time never exceeding 30 days 
all inmates except those in maximum security must receive 
eight hours a day of meaningful activity to include vocational 
training education and work 
no prison may use doublecelling or putting more than one 
inmate in any cell except in the face of dire emergencies such as 
riots or fires regardless of the cells size dormitories must 
provide 60 square feet for each inmate 
liberal visitation policies must be used including allowing 
kissing and embracing when feasible 
us district judge juan g burciaga in 1988 turned down the 
states request to modify the consent decree and the 10th us 
circuit court of appeals upheld his ruling last sept 15 
in the appeal acted on today new mexico attorney general hal 
stratton argued the issues in this case vitally affect the 
ability of the states to administer their prisons free from 
longterm daytoday federal court control over matters not 
governed by federal law 
the states appeal called the 1980 consent decree outmoded 
because more recent high court rulings make clear that the decrees 
standards go far beyond any federal law requirements 
the appeal was supported in a friendofthecourt brief 
filed by 39 states and puerto rico 
the case is carruthers vs duran 89786 
</TEXT>
