<TEXT>
chinas trade figures improved in 1989 but 
economic sanctions imposed after the crackdown on the prodemocracy 
movement severely limited access to foreign loans and technology a 
trade official said today 
liu xiangdong spokesman for the ministry of foreign economic 
relations and trade said exports reached 4327 billion up 65 
percent from 1988 while imports declined by 39 percent to 3827 
billion 
but he said economic sanctions imposed by western nations after 
the military crushed the studentled prodemocracy movement in june 
caused foreign loan agreements to drop by 51 percent to 48 
billion 
he said the number of technology import contracts 328 was down 
25 percent due to tougher restrictions on technology transfers to 
china following the crackdown the value of those contracts dropped 
18 percent to 29 billion 
liu noted that some developed countries recently indicated they 
will lift sanctions but he said no action had been taken and we 
do not have any unrealistic fantasies 
china must stress selfreliance in its modernization drive he 
said 
the nations chief economic planning official echoed lius 
sentiments in a speech to businessmen in tokyo today 
the population of china is large and the issues the chinese 
people face are serious and tough said zou jiahua head of 
chinas state planning commission 
we need a stable and united government and a stable 
environment to carry through construction of socialism he told 
the japan association for the promotion of international trade 
zou who arrived in japan last week at the invitation of the 
trade group is the first highlevel chinese official to visit 
since the crackdown 
he said chinas lifting of martial law in beijing on jan 11 was 
evidence of stability 
the move was widely seen as a gesture aimed at bringing foreign 
investors back to china and persuading western governments to drop 
sanctions imposed after the june crackdown 
the united states reacted by dropping opposition to world bank 
loans for basic human needs and japan has indicated it will 
renew talks on a credit package for development projects 
liu said china had not signed one foreign assistance contract 
since last springs political turmoil 
he said imports were down because of the drop in technology 
purchases and austerity policies that have sharply reduced demand 
and economic growth 
as a consequence trade with japan fell 5 percent to about 14 
billion liu said uschinese trade was up 137 percent to 94 
billion however 
liu said not one of the 899 beijingbased foreign firms 
registered with the trade ministry left after the military 
crackdown and that 71 more firms had registered since june 
he said there were 5784 new projects involving foreign 
investment nationwide last year down by 27 percent 
