<TEXT>
a sharply divided supreme court ruled today in 
the case of a convicted white rapist that fairtrial rights are not 
violated when blacks are excluded from serving as jurors 
but the 54 ruling in an illinois case did not leave white 
defendants powerless to challenge the exclusion of blacks from 
their juries the court left unanswered whether racebased 
exclusions ever discriminate unlawfully against white defendants 
the dissenters said the decision condones racial bias in jury 
selection 
the court in 1986 ruled that when prosecutors disqualify 
potential jurors based on their race it violates the 14th 
amendments ban on discrimination the amendment guarantees equal 
protection under the law 
the 1986 case involved a black defendant and black jurors and 
was not based on the sixth amendments guarantee to be tried by a 
fair crosssection of the community 
that ruling dramatically curtailed the traditionally broad power 
of prosecutors to eliminate prospective jurors from trials by using 
peremptory or automatic challenges 
justice antonin scalia writing for the court in todays case 
said race as such has nothing to do with the legal issue in this 
case 
scalia said the constitutions sixth amendment right to be tried 
by a jury representing a fair crosssection of the community was 
not violated by excluding blacks from the trial of daniel holland 
a chicagoarea white man sentenced to 85 years in prison for rape 
kidnaping and armed robbery 
hollands sixth amendment claim would be just as strong if the 
object of the exclusion had been not blacks but postmen or 
lawyers or clergymen or any number of other identifiable 
groups scalia said 
the sixth amendment no more forbids the prosecutor to strike 
jurors on the basis of race than it forbids him to strike them on 
the basis of innumerable other generalized characteristics he 
said 
justice thurgood marshall in a dissenting opinion said the 
majority today insulates an especially invidious form of racial 
discrimination in the selection of juries the elimination of 
racial discrimination in our system of criminal justice is not a 
constitutional goal that should lightly be set aside 
he was joined by justices william j brennan and harry a 
blackmun 
justice john paul stevens in a separate dissent said a jury 
that is the product of such a racially discriminatory selection 
process cannot possibly be an impartial jury within the meaning of 
the sixth amendment 
joining scalia were chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices sandra day oconnor byron r white and anthony m kennedy 
in hollands case the only two blacks among the more than 30 
prospective jurors were excluded by the prosecution from serving on 
the allwhite panel that convicted him 
prosecutors said they were not motivated by racial 
considerations when they used their peremptory challenges to 
exclude the two blacks a man and a woman from the jury 
holland was convicted of raping and kidnaping a des plaines 
ill teenage girl on may 4 1980 
the illinois supreme court ruled that because holland is white 
he lacked legal standing to raise the issue of whether race played 
a part in the exclusion of the blacks 
the us supreme court ruled otherwise today scalia said a 
white criminal defendant has as much legal standing as a black to 
claim a sixth amendment violation in such a case 
but scalia said hollands claim fails because eliminating a 
distinctive group from a jury does not deprive the defendant of a 
representative jury in violation of the constitution 
the court has never held that representativeness cannot be 
diminished by allowing both the accused and the state to eliminate 
persons thought to be inclined against their interests scalia 
said 
the case is holland vs illinois 885050 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

