<TEXT>
the supreme court today scuttled a federal 
lawsuit stemming from the collapse of the old court savings amp loan 
association in maryland saying state courts may handle suits based 
on a federal antiracketeering law 
the justices unanimously ruled that lower federal courts rightly 
dismissed the suit because similar suits were being handled by 
state courts in maryland 
old courts collapse helped trigger a savings and loan crisis in 
maryland in 1985 and led to criminal convictions for former owners 
jeffrey levitt jerome cardin and allan pearlstein 
levitt was sentenced to 30 years in prison for stealing 147 
million from the thrift institution cardin 15 years for stealing 
385000 and pearlstein eight years for stealing 640786 
civil suits seeking hundreds of millions of dollars were filed 
against the owners in federal and state courts some of those 
claims have been settled out of court 
old court owners and others including a law firm and an 
accounting firm that worked for the savings and loan were accused 
in the suits of the largest financial fraud in marylands history 
a group of 30 maryland nonresidents old court investors who 
live in seven other states sued in federal court they alleged 
among other things that the defendants violated the federal 
racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations act rico 
the law although primarily aimed at fighting organized crime 
has been used increasingly in lawsuits against businesses 
the investors federal suit was dismissed by a federal judge 
because other suits alleging rico violations were then pending in 
maryland state courts 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals upheld the dismissal and 
todays decision said the appeals court was right the ruling 
resolves conflicting rulings on the issue among the nations 
federal appeals courts 
we hold that state courts have concurrent jurisdiction to 
consider civil claims arising under rico justice sandra day 
oconnor wrote for the court 
nothing in the language structure legislative history or 
underlying policies of rico suggests that congress intended 
otherwise she said 
the case is tafflin vs levitt 881650 
