<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to review a 
former high school wrestling coachs 15yearold libel lawsuit 
against an ohio newspaper a case that reached the high court twice 
previously 
the justices said they will review an ohio supreme court ruling 
that threw out michael milkovichs 1975 suit against the news 
herald of lake county 
the willoughbybased newspaper is published by the lorain 
journal co it and onetime sports writer ted diadiun now an editor 
with the plain dealer in cleveland were sued over a 1975 column 
that accused milkovich and a former school administrator of lying 
during a court hearing 
milkovich was coaching maple heights high schools wrestling 
team at a 1974 home meet against mentor high school when a melee 
involving both teams and spectators erupted several wrestlers were 
hospitalized 
diadiun who was at the meet wrote several articles criticizing 
milkovichs conduct 
in a jan 8 1975 column diadiun accused the coach and h don 
scott then superintendent of maple heights public schools of 
lying to a judge who had overturned disciplinary measures against 
the maple heights team 
during extensive litigation milkovich won two preliminary 
rounds before the ohio supreme court and both victories were left 
intact by the nations highest court 
in a 1984 decision the ohio court ruled that diadiuns 
statements about milkovich were reported as facts not opinion 
expressions of opinion generally are immune from libel lawsuits 
but in ruling on scotts related libel suit two years later the 
ohio supreme court reversed its 1984 ruling and said diadiuns 
statements were expressions of his opinion 
in an unusual move the ohio court used its aug 6 1986 
decision in scotts case to doom as well milkovichs suit against 
the paper and diadiun 
the state court voting 43 and applying a totality of the 
circumstances test said the suedover column is immune under 
the constitutions freespeech guarantees from liability 
one factor discussed by the ohio court was the columns 
placement on the papers sports page what the court called a 
traditional haven for cajoling invective and hyperbole 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for milkovich urged the 
justices to use his case to clarify how courts should determine 
whether allegedly libelous statements are to be viewed as fact 
or opinion 
but lawyers for the newspaper and diadiun said the appeal should 
be rejected because the ohio court had based its decision not only 
on the federal constitution but on the ohio constitution as well 
a states highest court not the us supreme court is the 
ultimate interpreter of that states constitution 
the case is milkovich vs lorain journal co 89645 
