<TEXT>
the supreme court giving another signal that 
it is willing to allow random drug testing of government employees 
in sensitive positions today rejected appeals by justice 
department employees and civilian army counselors 
the justices in their first drugtesting rulings last march 
upheld drug and alcohol tests for railway workers involved in 
accidents and for us customs service employees applying for jobs 
in drug enforcement or jobs that require carrying a gun 
neither of those rulings however determined the 
constitutionality of randomly administered drug tests 
today the court without comment rejected appeals by justice 
department employees with top security clearance and civilian army 
drug and alcohol counselors who said mandatory random tests violate 
their privacy rights 
in other action the court 
ruled in the case of a convicted white rapist that fairtrial 
rights are not violated when blacks are excluded from serving as 
jurors 
but the 54 ruling in an illinois case did not leave white 
defendants powerless to challenge the exclusion of blacks from 
their juries the court left unanswered whether such racebased 
exclusions ever discriminate unlawfully against white defendants 
the dissenters said the decision condones racial bias in jury 
selection 
agreed to decide whether nuclear industry whistleblowers 
who say they were disciplined for complaining about lax safety may 
sue under state personalinjury laws 
the justices said they will review a north carolina case in 
which a federal appeals court said such workers must sue under a 
special federal law 
agreed to use a decadelong dispute over the rights of haitian 
refugees to decide when the government must pay legal fees to 
people who sue it successfully 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal aimed 
at limiting such fees 
refused to require arbitration for hundreds of thousands of 
federal workers when they are fired demoted or otherwise 
disciplined 
the court without comment rejected appeals by a labor union 
and the federal labor relations authority seeking broader job 
protection for federal employees 
in one of the drugtesting cases acted on today the us 
circuit court of appeals here upheld random urinalysis for several 
hundred civilian drug counselors in the army 
the appeals court said requiring them to submit to the tests is 
reasonable because counselors who use illicit drugs are bound to be 
unsympathetic to their mission of helping others overcome drug 
addiction 
the army maintains a legitimate interest in ensuring that its 
employees are allegiant to their essential mission the appeals 
court said 
random testing for thousands of other civilian army workers who 
fly and service planes and helicopters and hold law enforcement 
jobs was upheld by the appeals court also those employees did not 
appeal 
the drug counselors appeal was made by their union the 
national federation of federal employees 
in the case involving topranked justice department employees 
the appeals court said the governments interest in protecting 
topsecurity information outweighs individual privacy interests 
but the appeals court barred the government from imposing random 
tests for other department employees such as federal prosecutors 
and workers with access to grand jury information 
bush administration lawyers did not ask the supreme court to 
permit more widespread drug testing by overturning that portion of 
the appeals court ruling 
but administration lawyers urged the court not to disturb the 
rulings that permit testing of the army drug counselors and justice 
department employees with top security clearance 
the counselors occupy a critical place in the armys 
comprehensive drug program the government lawyers said 
as for justice department employees with top security clearance 
the government said it is reasonable to require those entrusted 
with the governments most closely held secrets to be drug free 
the testing of federal employees stems from a 1986 order issued 
by thenpresident ronald reagan calling for a drugfree federal 
workplace 
the supreme courts 1989 drugtesting rulings and the cases 
acted on today do not bear directly on workers in private 
employment 
congress is reviewing proposed legislation that would set 
federal standards for testing by private businesses a number of 
states already have drugtesting laws some of them give more 
privacy protection to workers than the federal proposal 
army counselors and justice department employees whose tests 
show they have used drugs are subject to disciplinary action or 
even firing but do not face criminal prosecution as a result of 
the tests 
the cases are national federation of federal employees vs 
cheney 89635 and bell vs thornburgh 89679 
