<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that lawyers in 
the nations capital violated antitrust law when they went on 
strike to demand higher pay from the city for representing poor 
criminal defendants 
by a 63 vote the court said the boycott was a plain 
violation of antitrust laws 
the case now goes back to a lower court to consider reinstating 
an order by the federal trade commission that prohibits the lawyers 
from engaging in similar conduct in the future 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court rejected 
arguments that the attorneys boycott is protected by the 
constitution 
the undenied objective of their boycott was an economic 
advantage for those who agreed to participate no matter how 
altruistic the motives may have been he said 
stevens said the case is different from a boycott by blacks in 
mississippi who refused to buy from white merchants the court in 
1982 ruled that the first amendement protected those boycotters 
against antitrust damages 
in a dissenting opinion joined by justice thurgood marshall 
justice william j brennan said todays ruling goes too far in 
limiting freeexpression rights 
brennan said the lawyers may have violated antitrust law but he 
said the ftc must first prove the attorneys exerted market 
power that they were capable of exercising economic control 
through concerted action to determine how much the city paid them 
justice harry blackmun also dissented 
the lawyers are members of the superior court trial lawyers 
association the group organized a boycott in 1983 to pressure the 
district of columbia government to increase the hourly compensation 
paid to attorneys who represent indigent criminal defendants 
the attorneys some 100 lawyers who represent most of the citys 
poor criminal defendants had been receiving 30 an hour for time 
in court and 20 an hour for outofcourt work they won a 25 per 
hour increase after a twoweek boycott in which nearly all of them 
refused to accept new cases 
the boycott created a crisis for the city swamping the city 
public defenders office with criminal cases the city government 
agreed to the higher hourly rate at an annual cost to taxpayers of 
more than 4 million 
the private lawyers who boycotted represent 85 percent of the 
poor defendants the remaining defendants are represented by the 
public defender service thirdyear law students or in a small 
number of cases lawyers volunteering to work free 
the ftc ruled after the socalled strike that the lawyers had 
engaged in price fixing and an illegal boycott and ordered them not 
to engage in similar conduct again 
the us circuit court of appeals here set aside the ftc 
decision and ordered the agency to conduct further study to 
determine whether the lawyers exerted market power 
the case is ftc vs superior court trial lawyers association 
881198 
</TEXT>
