<DOCNO> AP900122-0097 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken monday by the supreme court 
 
drug tests 
 
the court giving another signal that it is willing to allow 
random drug testing of government employees in sensitive positions 
rejected appeals by justice department employees and civilian army 
counselors 
the justices in their first drugtesting rulings last march 
upheld drug and alcohol tests for railway workers involved in 
accidents and for us customs service employees applying for jobs 
in drug enforcement or jobs that require carrying a gun 
neither of those rulings however determined the 
constitutionality of randomly administered drug tests 
today the court without comment rejected appeals by justice 
department employees with top security clearance and civilian army 
drug and alcohol counselors who said mandatory random tests violate 
their privacy rights 
the cases are national federation of federal employees vs 
cheney 89635 and bell vs thornburgh 89679 
 
jurors 
 
the court ruled in the case of a convicted white rapist that 
fairtrial rights are not violated when blacks are excluded from 
serving as jurors 
but the 54 ruling in an illinois case did not leave white 
defendants powerless to challenge the exclusion of blacks from 
their juries the court left unanswered whether such racebased 
exclusions ever discriminate unlawfully against white defendants 
the dissenters said the decision condones racial bias in jury 
selection 
the case is holland vs illinois 885050 
 
nuclear safety 
 
the court agreed to decide whether nuclear industry 
whistleblowers who say they were disciplined for complaining 
about lax safety may sue under state personalinjury laws 
the justices said they will review a north carolina case in 
which a federal appeals court said such workers must sue under a 
special federal law 
the case is english vs general electric 89152 
 
legal fees 
 
the court agreed to use a decadelong dispute over the rights of 
haitian refugees to decide when the government must pay legal fees 
to people who sue it successfully 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal aimed 
at limiting such fees 
the case is commissioner of ins vs jean 89601 
 
arbitration 
 
the court refused to require arbitration for hundreds of 
thousands of federal workers when they are fired demoted or 
otherwise disciplined 
the court without comment rejected appeals by a labor union 
and the federal labor relations authority seeking broader job 
protection for federal employees 
the cases are national treasury employees union vs treasury 
department 89610 and federal labor relations authority vs 
treasury department 89758 
 
lawyers 
 
the court ruled that lawyers in the nations capital violated 
antitrust law when they went on strike to demand higher pay 
from the city for representing poor criminal defendants 
by a 63 vote the court said the boycott was a plain 
violation of antitrust laws 
the case now goes back to a lower court to consider reinstating 
an order by the federal trade commission that prohibits the lawyers 
in washington from engaging in similar conduct in the future 
the case is ftc vs superior court trial lawyers association 
881198 
 
farmers 
 
the court turned away a challenge to a banks foreclosure on an 
oregon couple seeking to hold onto a farm in their family since 
1853 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that the federal 
law myron and jane harper relied on in their legal fight gives only 
the government not farmers the right to sue 
a federal appeals court ruling in the harpers case set binding 
law in nine western states and involves a farmloan program 
totaling over 50 billion nationwide 
the case is harper vs federal land bank of spokane 89863 
 
voting rights act 
 
the court ruled that a bibb county ga school bond referendum 
attacked by blacks as a violation of the federal voting rights act 
was legal 
the court without waiting to hear arguments in the case upheld 
a ruling that permitted the countys voters to approve 29 million 
to aircondition existing schools and build a new high school 
the justices decision was not accompanied by any written 
opinion there was no recorded dissenting vote 
the case is lucas vs townsend 89400 
 
abortion pickets 
 
the court refused to revive a federal civil rights lawsuit by 
five people prosecuted for antiabortion picketing outside a san 
diego medical clinic 
the justices without comment let stand a decision dismissing 
allegations that the clinics operators violated the pickets 
freespeech rights 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals last june 23 threw out 
11800 awards each of the five pickets had won in a federal trial 
the case is collins vs womancare 89819 
 
home addresses 
 
the court refused to let public employee labor unions get from 
the government the home addresses of federal workers 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that the 
workers privacy would be violated if government agencies are 
forced to divulge the information to the unions 
the cases are american federation of government employees vs 
department of health and human services 89444 national treasury 
employees union vs treasury department 89566 and federal labor 
relations authority vs treasury department 89853 
 
libel suit 
 
the court today agreed to review a former high school wrestling 
coachs 15yearold libel lawsuit against an ohio newspaper a case 
that reached the high court twice previously 
the justices said they will review an ohio supreme court ruling 
that threw out michael milkovichs 1975 suit against the news 
herald of lake county 
the case is milkovich vs lorain journal co 89645 
 
savings and loan 
 
the court scuttled a federal lawsuit stemming from the collapse 
of the old court savings amp loan association in maryland saying 
state courts may handle suits based on a federal antiracketeering 
law 
the justices unanimously ruled that lower federal courts rightly 
dismissed the suit because similar suits were being handled by 
state courts in maryland 
the case is tafflin vs levitt 881650 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

