<TEXT>
a graduate student was engaged in no 
juvenile prank when he created a worm program that paralyzed 
thousands of computers throughout the nation in 1988 a prosecutor 
contended this morning 
robert t morris 25 of arnold md is the first person 
brought to trial under a section of the 1986 computer fraud and 
abuse act that makes it a felony to break into a federal computer 
network and prevent authorized use of the system closing arguments 
in his federal trial began this morning 
ellen meltzer a trial lawyer for the us justice department 
said morris deliberately stole computer passwords from hundreds of 
people so the worm could break into as many computers as possible 
and she said morris who had testified that he never intended 
for the worm program to cause such harm took deliberate and 
conscious steps to make the rogue program difficult to detect and 
eradicate 
this was not a mistake she said robert morris worked 
diligently at creating this worm at trying to make it better 
but morris lawyer thomas guidoboni contended in his closing 
arguments that didnt intend to cause and did not cause permanent 
damage to any computer files when he unleased the worm 
there was no work lost work was delayed thats the bottom 
line guidoboni said 
he said that once morris realized the worm had gone berserk he 
took steps to try to stop it when that failed guidoboni said 
morris had friends send out a message on an electronic bulletin 
board with instructions how to defeat the worm 
does a person who intends unauthoritized use or to cause a 
system to crash send out a message to stop it of course not 
guidoboni said 
following this mornings closing arguments us district court 
judge howard munson sent the jury to lunch he was expected to 
instruct jurors and give them the case this afternoon 
there is mixed feeling among those who testified over whether 
the suspended cornell university graduate student should be 
severely punished for what he said was an experiment that ran out 
of control 
i dont think he did anything wrong said paul graham a 
government witness who became friends with morris at harvard and 
knew of morris work on the worm 
graham said morris should not be punished because the worm was 
an intellectual experiment common among computer security 
students and the only practical way to test whether security holes 
they find really exist 
a lot of computer security people while in graduate school 
spend time breaking into systems the government has decided it 
doesnt want them to do this anymore graham said they want 
them to learn about computer security from reading books 
but eugene spafford a purdue university computer ethics 
professor who has written about the worm and testified as a 
government witness said morris committed vandalism and should be 
punished accordingly 
he said morris defense that he didnt mean to paralyze the 
internet network which links computers at major universities nasa 
and several military facilities is like an arsonist saying he 
didnt mean for the fire he started to cause any damage 
most of the nearly dozen computer systems managers from 
facilities attacked by the worm said morris should be convicted but 
should not be dealt a harsh sentence 
id like to see an uncontested conviction and a light 
sentence said michael muuss leader of the advanced computer 
systems team at the us army ballistics research laboratory in 
aberdeen md 
i think the conviction would be a deterrent enough for others 
thinking about something like this he said 
morris admitted last thursday on the witness stand that he 
designed the worm specifically to infect internet he said the worm 
was an experiment that turned into a dismal failure because of 
a programming error he made that caused it to replicate wildly once 
it entered a computer 
it took several days to eliminate the worm the rogue program 
was originally termed a computer virus but unlike viruses it 
did not require a host program to reproduce 
although the indictment charged the worm did about 1000 in 
damage computer experts estimated that the time computers were 
down and the labor needed to combat the worm cost 5 million to 12 
million 
the worm was only supposed to break into a handful of the 
180000 computers on internet and then just leave a single copy of 
itself in all but a few machines morris said 
it was a mistake and im sorry were morris last words as 
he stepped off the witness stand 
