<TEXT>
reforms by the south african government 
and upheaval in eastern europe have caught the exiled african 
national congress groping for new strategies to wage a political 
rather than military struggle 
the anc the main guerrilla movement fighting white rule in 
south africa recently held a policy review conference in lusaka 
but announced no new proposals to counter reforms by president fw 
de klerk that have eased pressure on his government 
the anc continues to focus on hardline strategies such as its 
largely ineffectual bombing campaign and efforts to increase 
sanctions against south africa but these policies are generating 
little enthusiasm at a time when de klerk has been advocating 
negotiations with blacks and raising the possibility that he might 
lift the 30year ban on the anc 
looking at our situation realistically we must admit that we 
do not have the capacity within our country to intensify the 
armed struggle in any meaningful way said anc 
secretarygeneral alfred nzo 
he urged the guerrilla group not to trail behind events with 
our feet shackled by old perceptions and a fear to confront a new 
reality 
the ancs support among millions of black south africans is 
probably as strong as its been in its 78year history including 
the last three decades in exile most observers believe the anc 
would win elections if south africas 28 million blacks were 
allowed to vote 
the group also has good relations with most leading powers in 
the east and west and solid backing from black african states 
however the anc must readjust to changes in eastern europe and 
the soviet union traditionally their biggest backers and main 
weapons suppliers but now moving away from active involvement in 
faraway conflicts 
south african academic philip nel a soviet expert said 
officials in moscow have conveyed to the anc the soviets would 
maintain support for the movement only on condition that the anc 
commit itself clearly to a political program which could lead to a 
negotiated stabilization in south africa 
the anc conference highlighted generational and tactical 
differences among its members and uncertainty about how to approach 
potential negotiations after so many years of rejecting all 
proposals by the government 
many senior anc leaders are in their 60s and 70s and its 
president oliver tambo 71 is recovering from a stroke members 
of the older generation are reserved in demeanor wear suits at 
public events stress the importance of dialogue and stress that 
the armed struggle came about only as a last resort after the anc 
was outlawed in 1960 
most of the 1000 rankandfile members at the conference were 
