ussoviet arms talks resumed monday and 
negotiators expressed confidence they could meet the malta summit 
goal of completing a treaty on longrange nuclear weapons this year 
round 13 of the 5yearold negotiations on strategic nuclear 
arms and space weapons began with a meeting of delegation chiefs 
richard burt of the united states and yuri nazarkin of the soviet 
union 
a joint statement said both hope it will be possible during 
this round to make substantial progress on those issues where 
differences remain 
burt and nazarkin signed an agreement allowing trial inspections 
of each others nuclear warheads with the goal of finding ways to 
make sure the number of warheads on each missile does not exceed 
the limit 
its a good way to start burt said after the 35minute 
meeting 
nazarkin nodded and noted the inspection agreement was the 
fourth trial measure agreed upon by the negotiators the three 
others covered notification of maneuvers procedures to identify 
bombers carrying airlaunched cruise missiles and reciprocal 
demonstration of missile identification techniques 
the treaty resulting from the negotiations called start is 
intended to reduce the number of longrange missiles on each side 
by 30 to 50 percent negotiators have agreed on limits of 1600 
delivery vehicles missiles and bombers and 6000 nuclear 
warheads 
presidents bush and mikhail s gorbachev agreed at the malta 
summit in december that all major outstanding issues should be 
resolved by their next meeting in june and a start treaty should be 
signed by years end 
its constructive pressure burt said and added later that 
he was very optimistic the summit goals could be achieved this 
year 
