<TEXT>
officials in charge of the 5monthold savings 
and loan bailout are coming under increasing pressure to act more 
quickly on what amounts to the largest thrift institution and real 
estate sale in history 
the resolution trust corp created aug 9 when president bush 
signed the bailout legislation hit the ground running with an 
initial flurry of action within two months it had disposed of 33 
failed sampls out of the 262 it inherited 
but in the three months since then its disposed of only seven 
and its portfolio of failed sampls is growing faster than its list of 
resolutions 
at the end of last week it had sold a total of 40 institutions 
but still held 302 institutions with assets totaling 113 billion 
and in coming months it expects to take control of an additional 
200 bankrupt thrifts 
the house banking committee on tuesday opens three days of 
hearings into the administrations conduct of the bailout the 
senate banking committee is following with a fourth session next 
monday 
legislators and analysts are criticizing the administration for 
not doing more a marked contrast from the generally favorable 
reception bailout officials received during the last big round of 
congressional oversight hearings in october 
speed is crucial said professor paul horvitz of the 
university of houston these insolvent institutions are losing 
money but much more important than that is theyre also 
affecting the market and imposing losses on solvent institutions 
democrats on the banking panel are faulting resolution trust 
corp officials for being too afraid of the kind of withering 
criticism that hamstrung and ultimately forced the resignation of 
m danny wall who as chairman of the now defunct federal home loan 
bank board handled the disposal of 223 institutions in 1988 
its a politically charged area and theyre being extremely 
perhaps overly cautious said rep charles schumer dny a 
member of the banking committee theyre very troubled and 
worried about doing anything and often the bureaucratic response to 
that is dont just stand there do nothing 
the message we have to get across is inaction is not an 
alternative said rep bruce vento dminn who heads a house 
task force overseeing the bailout we didnt appoint them to be 
in a popularity contest we appointed them to do a job 
critics also cite the cumbersome administrative structure 
created by the sampl bill 
policy and purse strings are controlled by a board chaired by 
the secretary of the treasury however the corporations work is 
supervised by the federal deposit insurance corp an independent 
agency that insures bank and sampl deposits 
theres a fundamental structural problem said bert ely a 
financial institutions analyst in alexandria va ultimately 
whos in charge 
l william seidman who is chairman of both the fdic and 
resolution trust corp conceded that the administrative structure 
has slowed the cleanup process but he stressed the enormity of the 
agencys task 
youre setting up a new organization that had zero employees 
five months ago already its the equivalent of the secondlargest 
financial institution after citicorp in the country he said 
this month the corporation put 51 of its institutions on the 
auction block bringing the total for sale up to 70 it also 
released a 3000page inventory of 30000 pieces of real estate 
available in 45 states 
we want to do things rapidly but we also want to do things 
right seidman said overall i think our crew has 
accomplished quite a bit 
the corporation hopes to complete the sales in the second 
quarter but after that says it will face a cash crunch if the 
administration and congress cannot resolve the politically sticky 
question of how to raise working capital for the agency 
the sampl bill provided 50 billion to cover losses in insolvent 
but still open thrifts but the corporation needs an additional 
40 billion to 100 billion in working capital it would be repaid 
as the government sells assets from the failed sampls and would not 
increase the ultimate cost of the bailout 
they need more money and they need it sooner rather than 
later said robert litan of the brookings institution a policy 
research group in washington that sometimes advocates liberal 
positions the problem is the uncertainty over the budget 
treatment 
the administration wants to avoid inflating the budget deficit 
but congressional democrats argue that its is cheapest to borrow 
the money through the treasury which would count toward the 
deficit so far no one has come up with a compromise that will 
satisfy both sides 
