president bush said monday that he will 
nominate james kolstad as chairman of the national transportation 
safety board ending a 17month stalemate over leadership of the 
agency that investigates air sea and land transportation accidents 
kolstad 50 a former airline executive has been a member of 
the safety board since 1987 and its acting chairman since august 
1988 when jim burnett failed to win senate approval for a fourth 
twoyear term as chairman 
white house action on the nomination had been delayed while 
kolstad underwent an extended background check including scrutiny 
of his interim stewardship of the agency 
the board has been beset with bickering and other difficulties 
exacerbated by a tight budget and shrinking investigative staff 
board member joseph tribbe nall was killed nov 28 in a plane crash 
in caracas venezuela where he had gone to give a speech 
this long interim has been destabilizing and its good that 
the issue has been resolved said stephen hayes vice president 
of the air transport association which represents the major 
airlines we think hes certainly wellqualified and will be a 
very effective chairman of the board 
on capitol hill sen wendell ford dky the chairman of the 
senate aviation subcommittee said he was pleased with bushs move 
i believe mr kolstad has the necessary background 
qualifications and temperament to serve in this capacity mr 
kolstad will continue to promote the smooth operation of the board 
and i look forward to working with him as chairman ford said 
an aide to ford said the panel will schedule confirmation 
hearings on both kolstad and susan coughlin a bush nominee whose 
appointment to the board languished last year without a hearing 
kolstad was a white house aide and presidential advance man 
during the nixon administration he was director of congressional 
relations for the old civil aeronautics board from 197378 and 
later served as public affairs director for frontier airlines 
