flammability to build safety into making a choice said james 
hoebel head of the cpsc fire hazard and burn prevention division 
hoebels staff has recommended the commission require labeling 
that would classify adult pajamas nightgowns and robes by degree 
of fabric flammability 
i dont quarrel with their intent said larry k martin 
government relations director for the american apparel 
manufacturers association 
they want to provide some added safety to elderly people but 
you cant segregate nightwear for elderly people from what you and 
i wear added martin 
according to the cpsc there were 179 clothing fire deaths in 
1986 the last year for which figures are available adults aged 65 
and older were victims in all but 40 of those incidents and the 
clothing most frequently involved was sleepwear said hoebel 
were very concerned about trying to prevent those deaths 
said cpsc spokesman ken giles 
but martin said a simple flammability warning would accomplish 
the same goal as a complex system of fabric testing and rating 
weve recommended to the commission that they require a 
warning label that has a logo with a strike through it and a flame 
and language that says warning keep away from flame and other 
ignition source martin said 
labels are not required for childrens sleepwear but garments 
must meet a flammability performance standard that measures how 
quickly a garment stops burning 
cpsc testing includes burning with an open flame at least five 
10by3inch swatches from a garment no sample can burn more than 
seven inches before it stops burning and no one swatch can burn its 
full length for a garment to satisfy the government standard 
the american association of retired persons a lobbying group 
for the elderly prefers a performance standard but would back a 
classification system and a mandatory labeling program aarp 
volunteer james ryan told the commission last week 
