leader of the reformed communist party as polish communists begged 
the solidarityled government for protection from revenge 
before holding their last congress 
walesa a founder and leader of solidarity conferred with 
communist tadeusz fiszbach a deputy speaker of parliament who was 
ousted as gdansk party leader after the 1981 martiallaw crackdown 
here for his solidarity sympathies 
fiszbach has not said if he will bid to head the new party 
expected to emerge when the polish united workers party the 
communist party is dissolved during its 11th national congress 
opening saturday 
the only announced candidate is mieczyslaw f rakowski the 
current first secretary who seeks to bolster the partys dwindling 
role in polish politics with a new name and program 
if the slogans and ideas that mr fiszbach represents were 
valid during the last 10 years we would surely be further in 
reforming poland walesa said after the meeting 
he called fiszbach a man of reconciliation and the 
communist said there are common issues that do not divide us but 
unite us 
the two men did not indicate any agreement however on a major 
issue whether the buildings industries and other property 
accumulated by the communist party during 45 years of total power 
should be reclaimed for the public treasury 
walesa said the partys assets are public property 
one should not have an emotional approach fiszbach said 
i think the government should take up the issue and should 
consider the needs of newly created parties and the newly elected 
local governments 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki and his solidaritydominated 
cabinet have stopped government subsidies to political parities 
without moving to regain the property 
but there is considerable public demand to go further up for 
consideration thursday is a draft law submitted by 93 parliament 
members who want to take back party property 
the party congress coordinating committee protested monday and 
asked the government to guarantee us the elementary right to hold 
our congress 
an attempt to confiscate communist party property on the eve 
of its ending its life impedes the shaping of a rational 
arrangement of political forces in the country delegates said in 
a statement carried by the party daily trybuna ludu 
at the decisive moment we are becoming the focus of a 
propaganda and political attack 
in a climate of aggression there are attempts at revenge in a 
style that we assess as a relic of the past recently the slogan 
of nationalizing communist party property became the pretext for 
the attacks 
a commentary in trybuna ludu said parliaments adoption of the 
measure would be a revengeful abuse of freshly won power and 
end the short period of democracy in poland 
it said nationalizing party property would reinforce the 
arguments of the hardliners and be a political blow at the 
reformoriented current in the party 
over the weekend parliament began dismantling polands vast 
cooperative system attacked as a monopolistic bureaucratic 
vestige of communist power that must be pared down and opened to 
competition 
the lawmakers backed by the government voted to dissolve the 
central cooperative unions the top tier of a system that funneled 
small producers wares into a network of distributers ultimately 
regulated by supreme councils 
does a shoemaker in the countryside really need a chief 
manager in warsaw deputy urszula jarosz asked during the debate 
the official news agency pap reported 
the new law will remove regulations and restrictions imposed on 
producers by the central cooperative unions as part of radical 
economic reforms that aim to turn polands staggering socialist 
economy into one driven by market forces 
adoption of the draft law will break up the old structures 
and will encourage grassroots initiative pap quoted deputy 
marian kowal as saying 
