a woman who says she stopped wearing 
slacks to work due to her religious beliefs will challenge her 
dismissal by her employer who says trousers are safer on the job 
the lawsuit filed by the equal employment opportunity 
commission on bonnie mai owens behalf goes before us district 
judge thomas wiseman jr on wednesday 
i am a member of the apostolic pentecostal church ms owen 
of culleoka said in a statement filed with the court my church 
teaches and i believe for religious reasons that it is wrong for 
women to wear slacks 
heilquaker officials say they have an unwritten dress code 
requiring all employees to wear trousers for safety reasons and 
that ms owen was informed of this policy during orientation 
the company whose lewisburg plant makes sheet metal components 
for residential heating and cooling systems claims dresses might 
get caught in machinery 
lee fortier a safety inspector hired by the eeoc said the 
slowmoving assembly line on which ms owen worked poses little 
danger he said loose shirttails and carpentertype aprons worn by 
many male employees pose as much hazard as a dress 
ms owen wore slacks to work for nearly three years before 
reporting for work feb 19 1986 in a skirt she said she was told 
to go home and change clothes and was fired the next day after she 
refused 
