<TEXT>
sana north yemen ap north yemen and south yemen on monday 
began allowing citizens to move freely between the two countries 
their latest step toward eventual unification 
at the conclusion of a threeday meeting in sana prime 
ministers abdulaziz abdulghani of the capitalist north and yassin 
saeed noman of the communist south declared that citizens could 
cross without hindrance 
they also said all political prisoners would be freed 
immediately but gave no numbers 
the human rights organization amnesty international has reported 
that each nation holds dozens of people as political prisoners 
the statement from the threeday meeting which was held to 
outline steps to merging the countries also said the two 
governments foresaw a joint body of 33 ministries for the unified 
state 
the two red sea countries have been working for unity for more 
than a decade despite the difference in ideology between 
conservative north yemen and marxist south yemen 
but the unity drive gained impetus last year as the 
sovietbacked government in south yemen following the lead of 
other countries began leaning toward reform 
president ali abdullah saleh of north yemen and south yemeni 
socialist party secretarygeneral ali salem albeidh have decided 
that a joint constitution for the full merger should be prepared by 
their parliaments and put to a referendum in both countries no 
later than nov 30 
the north yemeni capital of sana has been designated as capital 
of the united country 
the border regions are rugged mountainous and mainly inhabited 
by tribes yemeni citizens in recent weeks have gained automatic 
telephone access to each others countries and there are reports 
of plans for a joint television program 
representatives of the nations today also requested that a 
financial and economic committee speed the drafting of single laws 
for customs currency banking taxes and other areas 
similar instructions were issued to ministries dealing with 
education judiciary information legislation foreign affairs and 
diplomatic representation and the interior 
asked about adjusting differences in economic systems between a 
relatively free north yemen and a socialist south noman said we 
shall be bound by the economic principles that will emerge in the 
constitution and political will 
</TEXT>
