<TEXT>
the navys search for a quieter nuclear 
submarine is causing a ruckus in this port town 
residents are divided over pentagon plans to measure the noise 
of seawolfclass attack submarines in the rich fishing grounds that 
support the towns economy 
on one side are those who support the project as a contribution 
to national defense on the other are those who say it would 
threaten the regions lucrative sport fishing industry and make 
ketchikan a potential target for nuclear attack the opponents also 
complain that the navy has no plan to deal with a nuclear accident 
in the isolated area 
its going to seriously hurt our economy as far as tourism 
sport and commercial fishing industry goes said resident jack 
lee one of the projects most outspoken critics 
lee added that the community also has some very valid concerns 
about safety about our inability to evacuate in light of the 
navys pathetic safety record 
supporters say those are the unfounded fears of a small but 
vocal minority in a town that has long welcomed visiting navy 
vessels with its fishing fleet and touristfilled cruise ships 
the activists are the kind you normally see on these antinuke 
things these bearded longhaired artists said ralph 
bartholomew a member of the ketchikan gateway borough assembly 
theyre the kind that arent producing much in the community 
theyre living off it 
concerns over the project have been raised far beyond the 
mountainous sprucecarpeted islands of southeastern alaska a 
lawsuit to halt the project is pending in federal court in 
washington dc and objections have been heard in the canadian 
parliament 
although the state has not officially approved the project the 
navy began clearing a site for a 127 million facility on tiny 
back island last fall 
beginning next year the navy plans to use a stretch of behm 
canal near back island for tests aimed at making us submarines 
the quietest in the world the site about 25 miles north of 
ketchikan and 688 miles north of seattle is within one of the most 
popular sport fishing grounds in alaska 
king salmon up to 40 pounds and halibut over 100 pounds are 
frequently caught in the sheltered waters of behm canal charter 
and resort operators fear the movement of submarines will scare 
away the fish and the fishermen 
gene romano a navy spokesman in seattle said the sub tests 
would be conducted periodically in one submarines would move 
between underwater microphones in another a bargemounted crane 
would suspend a submarine under water with its engines off while 
onboard equipment is turned on and off to test its contribution to 
the vessels noise level 
the acoustical testing of submarines is a critical factor in 
maintaining superiority in the submarine force romano said 
the navy argues that the task can best be done in the quiet 
islandprotected waters of behm canal a soundtesting range in 
puget sound near tacoma wash has become too noisy to be 
effective officials say 
development of the alaska site coincides with construction of 
the first seawolf submarine by general dynamics corp in groton 
conn its estimated cost is 17 billion 
romano would not say if back island was designed specifically 
with the seawolf in mind the site will be designed to test all 
types of navy submarines he said 
a lawsuit opposing the testing was filed by the foundation on 
economic trends a washington dcbased technology and military 
watchdog group ketchikan groups representing environmentalists 
sport fishermen natives and a wilderness resort joined the lawsuit 
us district judge joyce hens green declined to issue a 
preliminary injunction two months ago but said it appeared the 
navy had violated the national environmental policy act in planning 
the project her ruling on a request for a permanent injunction is 
expected soon 
romano said the navy has modified its plans to meet community 
concerns in response to fishing interests the navy has changed 
its proposed testing times and created a corridor in which fishing 
boats can move at slow speed and not have to wait for the tests 
obviously in todays age its almost impossible to have a 
major construction project thats not going to upset someone he 
said but we feel the majority of the people are in support of 
the project 
