<TEXT>
general motors corp will recall 244000 
fourcylinder pontiac fieros every one ever made because of a 
nagging enginefire problem that contributed to the companys 
decision to scuttle the twoseater 
the fiero was an immediate sales success in september 1983 but 
its demise at the end of the 1988 model year came nearly as 
quickly partly after consumer advocate ralph nader alleged engine 
problems led to fires 
general motors hasnt determined when the recall will take 
effect or what kind of repair work will be performed company 
spokesman tom pyden said monday 
weve notified nhtsa the national highway traffic safety 
administration of our intent to conduct a recall pyden said 
he said gm was working on the procedure for a recall and until 
that point it is premature to come out and notify owners and 
dealers 
tim hurd a spokesman for the national highway safety agency 
said monday the agency received a letter dated dec 28 1989 from 
gm saying the company would recall the cars hurd would not say if 
it was unusual that a month pass between the time the agency was 
notified and the time a recall is issued 
it is the second time the fourcylinder fiero has been recalled 
because of possible engine fires pontiac made about 100000 
sixcylinder fieros which will not be subject to the recall 
it is my understanding that the previous fix has not solved 
the problem of fires in fieros hurd said from his washington 
office im sure that gm is working as hard as it can in good 
faith to get this problem solved 
in 1987 gm recalled 125000 fourcylinder versions produced in 
the 1984 model year after engine fires occurred in one of every 400 
cars the company said engine connecting rods which link pistons 
to the crankshaft could blast through the side of the engine 
causing an oil leak which could cause a fire during that recall 
gm made some alterations including boosting oil capacity to four 
quarts from three and urging motorists to check the engine oil 
every time they got gasoline 
word of the recall was published friday in the national highway 
safety agencys monthly defect report gm was caught unaware that 
the notice would be published said spokesman reggie harris 
this is unusual normally we would make our own announcement 
when we have a program in place harris said 
gm began making the fiero at a plant in pontiac in january 1983 
for the 1984 model year the first car was rolled off the assembly 
line in july 1983 with a base price of 7999 
on march 1 1988 pontiac announced that fiero production would 
end with the 1988 model year when 24621 fieros were sold 
