a judge on monday rejected allegations 
that investigators broke the law when they staged a second raid on 
a palestinians apartment to hunt for evidence in the bombing of 
pan am flight 103 
scottish police want to compare clothing seized in the raids 
with shreds found in a suitcase believed to have contained the bomb 
which downed flight 103 over lockerbie scotland on dec 21 1988 
killing 259 people on board and 11 on the ground 
swedish police working with scottish investigators confiscated 
the clothes in a jan 12 raid on the apartment of mohammed abu 
talb who was sentenced last month to life in prison on separate 
charges related to terrorist bombings in northern europe four years 
ago 
prosecutor ulf forsberg said after the closeddoor hearing in 
uppsala 42 miles north of the capital stockholm that the clothes 
were overlooked when police took 10 plastic bags of clothing from 
abu talbs apartment in late november 
district court judge gunnar graberg ruled the confiscation was 
justified because talb has been named in the flight 103 
investigation said a court source who declined to be identified 
the source said talbs defense lawyer challenged the latest 
seizure in court claiming it was not legally founded because the 
suspicions against talb were not strong enough 
police have said they investigated the popular front for the 
