<DOCNO> AP900122-0206 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
delegates from the liberal republic 
of slovenia walked out of a communist party congress monday after 
being defeated on several key reform issues and the split in the 
party seemed to be irreconcilable 
the congress adjourned without setting a date for reconvening 
after leaders debated for nearly four hours at an emergency session 
on how to handle the crisis 
delegations from the republics of croatia macedonia and 
bosniahercegovina indicated late monday no possibility existed 
that the congress could continue the state tanjug news agency 
reported 
party president milan pancevski told exhausted delegates early 
tuesday that party leaders would keep working toward a solution and 
asked regional party bodies to do the same 
delegates from slovenia believe more autonomy should be granted 
the six republics and two provinces in a nation that was held 
together for decades by the will of president tito who died in 
1980 serbian communists equate the party with the country and say 
it must remain unified 
the congress was due to end tuesday 
the walkout came as delegates were headed for a vote on a reform 
policy document in which the party was to relinquish its 
45yearold guaranteed monopoly on power 
earlier monday the congress cast a preliminary vote on giving 
up its political stranglehold but that vote was on a proposed 
amendment to the draft text and was dependent on the documents 
final adoption 
the slovenians complained hardliners had watered down crucial 
reform points and the final draft did not take into account the 
republics drive for greater independence 
the split came after three days of bitter debate 
croatian party chief ivica racan demanded the congress suspend 
its work otherwise he said croatias delegation would refuse to 
vote on the reform document and other conference papers 
president slobodan milosevic of serbia largest of the six 
republics said suspending work would cause the party to be 
practically disbanded and decapitated 
the congress took a 30minute recess after milosevic finished a 
speech in which he warned of grave consequences for the communist 
party and the future of the country 
he urged the remaining delegates to adopt the reform document 
and choose a new leadership 
milan kucan a leading slovenian communist told journalists the 
breakup of the communist party is the only possible consequence 
of this action 
slovenian party spokesman peter bekes said his party would have 
a regional party conference feb 2 and establish an independent 
party on the basis of democratic socialism 
he predicted two or three parties would emerge from the split in 
the national organization 
ciril ribicic leader of the slovenian party said before the 
walkout the congress failed to accept any of his delegations ideas 
and we are not going to take part in the agony of the communist 
party in yugoslavia 
the document on which we pinned by far the highest hopes 
turned out to be far below expectations and lagging behind reforms 
offered by reformminded leftist parties in socialist east 
european countries 
ribicic said the congress failed to acknowledge the 
independence sovereignty and equality of slovenias communist 
party 
slovenia is the second smallest republic with 2 million 
residents serbia has 9 million people 
slovenia said it would take an ideological course independent of 
the national party ribicic said the regional party had decided to 
seek independence from the national organization 
communists in slovenia proposed the national party become a 
loose coalition of independent regional organizations but serbia 
opposed it milosevic wants a strong central party 
delegates overwhelmingly favored asking parliament to remove the 
constitutional provision that guarantees a power monopoly 
party secretary stefan korosec told the congress the old model 
of a monopolistic communist system has no historical future 
korosec a slovenian candidate for the party leadership said 
the end has come to authoritarian socialism 
he urged communists to catch up on the pace of democratic 
reforms in europe and accept that they no longer are yugoslavias 
sole political force bulgaria czechoslovakia east germany 
poland and hungary have abolished the leading role of the communist 
party in recent months as part of their democratic reforms 
mondays amendment said the national party should transform 
itself as soon as possible into a unified modern democratized 
political organization 
many delegates have recommended a split into a socialist party 
in the western european style and a traditional communist party 
dozens of independent groups have been formed the past year and 
the government has pledged to pursue democratic reforms leading to 
free multiparty elections 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

