producer barry weissler whose smash revival of gypsy starring 
tyne daly has money from tokyo broadcasting 
they would also like to be in the entertainment business 
weissler says so they have invested in records film and now 
live theater and our american musical theater is an area they 
cant duplicate in japan since they want to play these pieces in 
japan it serves them to be first in line for a potential 
presentation there 
suntory japans largest privately held corporation is the 
biggest japanese investor currently on broadway through its equal 
partnership agreement with the shubert organization the agreement 
begun in 1988 runs into 1992 each puts up equal amounts of money 
and will share profits or losses equally 
the shuberts have a similar arrangement with capital citiesabc 
the three organizations reportedly put up 15 million each for 
jerome robbins broadway which had a total price tag of 8 
million suntory plans to take the musical with its american cast 
to japan early next year 
the shubertsuntory partnership has its roots in a 1982 tour of 
japan underwritten by suntory by the broadway cast of 
dancin the show a collection of dances created by bob fosse 
was perfect for a foreign audience no knowledge of english was 
required and much of the music such as sing sing sing 
big noise from winnetka and yankee doodle dandy was 
familiar in many places around the world 
we maintained a contact through the years says schoenfeld 
chairman of the shubert organization which owns a major share of 
broadways theaters and has actively produced shows to fill them 
in 1988 when we announced we were doing jerome robbins 
broadway suntory contacted us they were very very impressed 
with robbins and this was before they saw anything or even knew 
what the show was about that led to a series of meetings and out 
of them evolved a longterm relationship 
the agreement gives the shubert organization the right to select 
the shows and there is no limit on the number of productions that 
can be done each year schoenfeld says suntory in turn will 
decide what shows they want to produce in japan depending on what 
they think will be suitable for japanese audiences 
at this time we dont have the knowledge to judge what 
