<TEXT>
jeanie karklin says she saved 1500 on her 
mothers funeral because a federal rule required the funeral 
director to give her an itemized price list she calls the rule a 
godsend 
the same rule required funeral director timothy simms to hand a 
price list to the parents of a 4yearold boy killed in a car 
accident simms felt it was a tasteless thing to do in the 
emergency room 
six years after it took effect the socalled funeral rule 
is under review by the federal trade commission and consumers and 
the funeral industry are split on whether it should be renewed or 
repealed the review began in may 1988 and ftc staff 
recommendations are expected this spring 
consumer groups want the rul strengthened arguing it gives 
people important information to help them make one of the biggest 
purchases of their lives at a time of stress and bereavement it 
costs next to nothing provides a great deal of consumer 
information and may have led to prices going down said lee 
norrgard of the american association of retired persons which has 
led the fight to retain and expand the rule 
the nations largest association of funeral directors 
meanwhile says the rule unnecessarily regulates daytoday 
business practices increases costs and hinders funeral directors 
ability to serve grieving customers sensitively 
the rule has placed an undeserved and unwarranted stigma on 
the nations funeral directors as unscrupulous and deceptive 
businessmen the national funeral directors association told the 
ftc calling for repeal 
the rule took effect in 1984 after more than a decade of debate 
and investigation into funeral practices and after the nfda sued 
unsuccessfully to block it but after living with it for more than 
five years some funeral directors and smaller trade groups are 
amenable to retaining it 
our memberships living with it very well said connie ryan 
president of the wisconsin funeral directors association and 
director of ryan funeral home in madison we havent had any 
difficulties 
the rule requires funeral directors to give customers an 
itemized price list at the start of discussions an itemized final 
statement of costs and to give price information over the phone if 
asked it also lets consumers purchase only what they want rather 
than packages that may include unnecessary extras and prohibits 
funeral directors from misrepresenting state requirements for 
caskets for cremation or the embalming of corpses 
americans each year arrange more than 2 million funerals with 
costs averaging 3000 before burial fees a funeral may be the 
third most expensive consumer purchase after a home and a car 
according to the ftc 
mrs karklin of houston said the price list she got as she 
arranged her mothers funeral in granby mo in 1986 helped her 
insist on reasonably priced items when the funeral director kept 
saying her dear departed loved one deserved more 
even though i knew beforehand what my rights were and i knew 
my mother had always been a strong and thrifty woman who never 
approved of excess of expense i felt more and more battered down 
by what he was saying i said to him thank god for your price 
list he didnt look very happy 
when people are aware of their rights under the rule they are 
able to be more selective in their funeral purchases even if they 
decide to spend as much money as they would otherwise said 
clifford brownstein executive director of the continental 
association of funeral and memorial societies 
the association which represents 150 memorial societies 
nationwide that help people get information and make plans is 
calling for better enforcement of the rule and its expansion to 
businesses such as cemeteries and crematories 
for people who are aware of it it has made them more 
knowledgeable consumers brownstein said but most people have 
never heard of it if you dont know its there how can you take 
advantage of it 
a 1988 study by the ftcs bureau of economics found that while 
most people got a price list at some point only about a third of 
funeral directors gave a price list and final cost statement in the 
required timely manner and did not make misrepresentations it 
found that average funeral spending rose 9 percent between 1981 and 
1987 after adjusting for inflation and concluded that while the 
rule did not necessarily cause the increase the data strongly 
suggests that the rule did not contribute to a reduction in funeral 
expenditures 
aarps norrgard questioned the ftcs analysis and said there is 
evidence prices may have gone down after adjusting for inflation 
in addition he said studies show that consumers who get price 
lists early tend to spend less even though they may not compare 
prices between funeral homes 
mary ponder of the national consumers league said the benefits 
have been limited because there is little to no enforcement by 
the ftc 
robert hardin executive director of the nfda said the price 
disclosure requirements have hindered funeral directors done 
nothing to benefit consumers and contribute to higher prices by 
adding paperwork and training demands 
the ftcs own study disproved its theory that consumers would 
spend less and shop around more with the rule he said adding that 
most people select a funeral home because they had a personal 
experience with the home or because of its reputation not based on 
price 
the whole concept of the ftc back in 1984 was to try to change 
the social mores of this country and to try to convince the 
consumer that theyre shopping for a car when theyre shopping for 
a funeral hardin said its not a consumer product its a 
very professional consumer service 
simms who owns the wilbur christensen funeral home in rockford 
ill said compliance with the rule has kept him from handling 
difficult cases such as the 1985 death of the 4yearold boy as 
sensitively as he would like 
to immediately hand someone a price list really becomes very 
awkward the funeral rule lacks the discretion of a judgment call 
by a professional 
aarp is pushing to extend the rule to cemeteries and to expand 
regulation of the booming preneed business in which people 
buy in advance to finance funeral or cemetery goods and services 
some prepaid contracts often sold by telephone direct mail and 
doortodoor arent covered by the funeral rule 
minimum standards would ensure that consumers know what 
contracts cover how the death benefits increase over time how 
secure the investments are and whether contracts can be canceled or 
transferred if people move norrgard said 
at an ftc hearing last year william jones of lucerne calif 
testified that prepaid plans should be better regulated to keep 
unscrupulous businesses from preying on the elderly jones said his 
87yearold mother was despondent and in early stages of senility 
when a salesman visited her home in winnemucca nev and persuaded 
her to pay 3105 over two years for a prepaid funeral 
the ftc has shown little inclination to get involved in 
additional regulation of preneed contracts but norrgard expressed 
hope these sales might be the subject of a separate rulemaking 
procedure later 
the ftc originally faced a november 1989 deadline for a decision 
on its review of the funeral rule but rescinded that because of the 
thousands of pages of comments reports exhibits and 
recommendations that have been submitted 
</TEXT>
