<TEXT>
james walters worked for the ap as a reporter 
and editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kent newland a cactus expert grows them mainly 
to enjoy the spectacular flowers and says hes sure that amateurs 
even city apartmentdwellers can do the same by following a few 
simple basics 
they are glorious things to see blooming just gorgeous the 
flowers may not live for more than a day or two but while they 
last theres nothing quite like it newland says and if you 
have enough of them they bloom so often you can have some in 
flower every day of the year 
he has no quarrel with folks who grow cactuses only for their 
unique shapes but says many dont realize flowers are possible 
within a year or so even on the small inexpensive ones sold at 
botanical gardens and nurseries 
newland who cant remember when i havent been in love with 
cactuses spent 14 years with the boyce thompson southwestern 
arboretum in superior and now is water resources specialist for 
phoenixs xeriscape programs 
for home growers he says success with cactus begins with 
selecting the proper types globular kinds as opposed say to 
columnar ones like saguaros or cereus or types like the prickly 
pears which need a lot of light 
better choices are mammillarias pincushions and similar 
types they need good light but not high amounts so theyll adapt 
grow and flower in a southfacing window while the large ones at 
best will exist 
indoors most people will be happiest with cactus that flourish 
in no larger than a 6 to 8inch pot such as hardbodied 
mammillarias like the oldlady cactus mammillaria hahniana or the 
mother of hundreds m cupressa 
after plant selection the trick to growing cactuses is good 
drainage i think more cactus are lost from underwatering than 
overwatering to encourage root systems you need to keep them 
fairly damp not soaking wet of course 
plants dont look very healthy if they havent been watered 
for six months because the root systems die newland says 
so how do you know when to water id put a finger on the soil 
and if it feels moist its probably all right water when it feels 
bone dry when a plant is starting to grow throwing out new spines 
or stems thats the time to encourage it with water and fertilizer 
to initiate flowers 
during such growing periods newland includes an allpurpose 
fertilizer every other watering applying about an eighth to a 
fourth of the recommended dosage to ensure good even amounts of 
growth for flower production while he doesnt use slowrelease 
fertilizers they would be fine in moderation 
growing medium is extremely important he says the big 
thing is to stay away from pureorganic potting soils even if the 
bag is labeled cactus mix theyre very hard to wet up and very 
hard to dry out however if you amend that potting soil with some 
sharp masonry sand and some perlite the plant should grow well 
but first make sure the water drains through the mixture id 
fill a test pot to an inch or so of the top with the mix without 
a plant tamp the mix as usual and fill it with water if you dont 
get water coming out of the drain hole within one or two minutes a 
cactus will slowly dry up and die in it so add more sand and try 
the new batch until it drains right 
a good starting point is about half organic matter 40 percent 
sand and 10 percent perlite blended well 
newland repots each new cactus discarding the former growing 
medium that way i know the soil mix is identical for all my 
cactuses and if there are some hidden insects i get rid of them 
before transplanting he also loosens the root ball to encourage 
the root system to expand 
pot size also is important you dont want to put a 2inch 
cactus in a 6inch pot put it in a 3inch or maybe a 4inch 
moving it along as it grows 
mealybugs have been known to ruin cactus collections almost 
overnight newland will use malathion or diazinon soil drench if 
necessary but believes the best way to avoid pests is to grow 
healthy plants like a human being if youre healthy youre less 
prone to disease 
 
</TEXT>
