<TEXT>
patients in the early stages of alzheimers 
disease suffer damage to a specific type of eye cell explaining 
why they often bump into things and have trouble reading despite 
2020 vision researchers say 
the incurable progressive brain disorder which causes 
premature dementia or senility doesnt substantially affect optic 
cells called p cells that are responsible for visual acuity but 
it causes degeneration of m cells essential for people to orient 
themselves in space according to the study published in the 
january issue of the journal ophthalmology 
just as charts of letters test visual acuity produced by p 
cells dr alfredo sadun said his team at the university of 
southern california developed a test to check the performance of m 
cells sadun said it might be used to help diagnose early stages of 
alzheimers disease which is estimated to afflict 8 percent of the 
us population over age 65 
optic nerves from 10 deceased alzheimers patients and the 
cadavers of 10 people without the disease were examined by sadun 
an associate professor of ophthalmology and neurological surgery 
retinal tissue from three alzheimers patients and two normal 
cadavers also were examined and 15 alzheimers patients with no 
known eye disease were given complete exams of the eyes and related 
parts of the nervous system 
the postmortems found optic nerve degeneration in eight of the 
10 alzheimers patients and none of the control cadavers the 
degeneration was mainly of m cells and related fibers 
the loss of m cells is consistent with the symptoms sadun found 
among living alzheimers patients difficulty in reading and 
spatial orientation despite an ability to see very small objects 
and colors and difficulty in detecting movements of objects and 
differences in shades 
</TEXT>
