<TEXT>
an oregon couple seeking to hold onto a farm 
in their family since 1853 today lost a supreme court challenge to 
a banks foreclosure 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that the federal 
law myron and jane harper relied on in their legal fight gives only 
the government not farmers the right to sue 
a federal appeals court ruling in the harpers case set binding 
law in nine western states and involves an farmloan program 
totaling over 50 billion nationwide 
the harpers raise hogs corn and small grains on their farm in 
oregons willamette valley 
in 1984 the harpers were unable to make all their loan payments 
on the farm the federal land bank of spokane now the farm credit 
bank of spokane moved to foreclose on the farm in january 1987 and 
a foreclosure sale was scheduled for nov 17 of that year 
the harpers staved off the sale by seeking bankruptcy law 
protection on nov 13 but their bankruptcy petition was dismissed 
in february 1988 and a sheriffs sale of the farm was held march 
18 1988 
in the interim the agricultural credit act of 1987 had been 
signed into law by thenpresident ronald reagan 
the act a major rehauling of the federally created farm credit 
service requires lenders of distressed loans to let borrowers 
know before any foreclosure can take place that their loans may 
be suitable for restructuring 
farm credit system lenders extend about 30 percent of all farms 
loans nationwide that percentage totals over 50 billion 
the harpers sued in federal court in april 1988 seeking to 
postpone final conveyance of their farmland to those who bought it 
at the foreclosure sale 
us district judge owen panner barred the harpers eviction 
from their farm ruling that the federal land bank of spokane had 
a duty under the 1987 law to weigh the costs of foreclosure 
against the costs of restructuring 
but the 9th us circuit court of appeals threw out the judges 
injunction last june 24 ruling that the 1987 law does not give 
individual farmers the right to sue lenders who allegedly violate 
it 
in writing the law congress did not say explicitly whether such 
lawsuits were permissible and the appeals court said we hold 
there is no implied private right of action 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the harpers said the 
san franciscobased 9th circuit courts ruling is at odds with a 
ruling last oct 5 by the st louisbased 8th us circuit court of 
appeals 
but lawyers for the federal land bank of spokane noted that the 
8th circuit panels decision has been set aside pending review by 
that entire appeals court 
the case is harper vs federal land bank of spokane 89863 
</TEXT>
