<TEXT>
delta air lines chairman ronald w allen said a 
25 percent drop in the companys net income during its second 
fiscal quarter resulted from higher fuel prices and lower income 
per mile from fares during the period 
allen said saturday that weak passengermile yields for 
thanksgiving and christmas usually two of the busiest times for 
the airline also contributed to the decrease 
for the three months ended dec 31 the second quarter in 
deltas fiscal year deltas net income was 642 million or 113 
a share during the same period a year earlier earnings were 852 
million or 173 a share 
operating revenue for the latest quarter was 205 billion up 
from 186 billion in the same period a year earlier 
but fuel costs rose from 2205 million in the second quarter of 
1988 to 3142 million in the latest threemonth period 
increases in fuel costs recently have been cited for fare hikes 
throughout the us airline industry 
fuel expenses rose 43 percent the result of a 34 percent jump 
in the average price of aircraft fuel allen said 
he also noted that the passengermile yields the money taken 
in per passenger for each mile flown were down about 1 percent 
during the typically busy holiday season for the recent quarter 
the yield was 1339 cents down from 1348 cents in the yearago 
report 
for the six months ended dec 31 delta said its net income was 
1974 million or 365 a share compared with 1851 million or 
376 a share a year earlier 
sixmonth revenue rose 13 percent to 422 billion from 374 
billion a year earlier 
