<TEXT>
sen alan cranston said monday he would 
introduce legislation to allow investors to sue the government if 
they fail in other efforts to recover losses from worthless junk 
bonds sold at lincoln savings amp loan association 
the california democrat facing his most serious political 
crisis because of his involvement with lincoln continued an attack 
that began last week blaming a former banking regulator for 
investors losses 
cranston said his legislation to be introduced this week would 
allow bond holders to file suit against the us government if they 
are unsuccessful in suits against lincoln parent american 
continental corp and company chief charles h keating jr 
the government is usually immune from such suits but cranston 
said there were precedents allowing lawsuits in cases of government 
negligence 
documents i have received from the office of thrift 
supervision in washington and the general accounting office are 
clearly enough evidence on which to bring a case of negligence 
against the government cranston said 
cranston spoke at the latest in a series of news conferences 
intended to deflect blame that had been aimed at him for investor 
losses stemming from the failure of the irvinebased lincoln 
cranston the senate majority whip is one five senators under 
investigation by the senate ethics committee for intervening with 
regulators on behalf of lincoln american continental of phoenix 
and keating keating and his family contributed 13 million to the 
senators and their causes 
three recent polls show cranstons popularity with california 
voters has plunged to its lowest level since he came to the senate 
in 1969 but he has promised to seek reelection next year 
nonetheless 
by focusing on the bondholders he hopes to disarm one of the 
most personally damaging allegations against him bondholders 
testimony that his intervention for keating made him partly 
responsible for their losses 
he spent much of last week attacking former chief sampl regulator 
edwin j gray as the main culprit in the failure of lincoln and the 
losses to bondholders many of them elderly people who lost their 
life savings 
cranston tried to paint what he called a picture of negligence 
by gray and his staff when gray headed the federal home loan bank 
board 
as ammunition cranston released a chronology by federal 
regulators that showed the bank board permitted american 
continental to sell its junk bonds at the thrifts offices even 
though regulators questioned the firms ability to repay 
bondholders 
the bonds unlike bank accounts at lincoln were not insured and 
became worthless when american continental filed for bankruptcy 
cranston said investors were victims of baitandswitch tactics 
that regulators should not have allowed 
state and federal officials say the bondholders mostly los 
angelesarea retirees were targeted by lincoln to switch nearly 
200 million of federally insured deposits into the uninsured junk 
bonds after federal examiners first recommended closing the 
irvinebased thrift in may 1987 
the 2 billionplus cost for protecting depositors with insured 
accounts not the bondholders is likely to be the most expensive 
thrift takeover in history 
