<TEXT>
housing and urban development secretary jack kemp 
told a home builders convention monday to avoid alarm over the 
industrys current slump 
a lot of the current doom and gloom is contrary to the 
facts kemp said i dont believe housing is going to be 
americas next crisis 
in a speech to the national association of home builders kemp 
acknowledged that last months 8 percent decline in housing starts 
the recent softening of real estate prices and the crisis in the 
savings and loan industry are an understandable cause for 
concern 
but he said efforts by the bush administration to lower interest 
rates and the proposed cut in the capital gains tax themes sounded 
by president bush in his speech friday to the nahb could help 
revive the fortunes of the industry 
both measures appear to have strong support in the industry as 
their mention in the speeches by bush and kemp drew applause 
a capital gains tax cut he said will reinvigorate the real 
estate market the equity market the bond market and other 
financial markets 
opponents of the cut say it would favor mainly big investors and 
people making more than 100000 a year 
what some on the left forget is that the capital gains tax 
doesnt just help old wealth its an incentive for the creation of 
new wealth kemp told the home builders 
