<TEXT>
the high cost of nursing home insurance places 
it out of reach for most older americans and demonstrates the need 
for a government program to protect people against the staggering 
costs of longterm care an advocacy group said monday 
the families usa foundation released a study saying that 84 
percent of americans from ages 65 to 79 cannot afford even a basic 
nursing home insurance policy and most companies do not issue 
policies to people age 80 and older 
executive director ron pollack called the findings shocking and 
said they bolster the case for a social insurance solution akin to 
social security spreading the benefits and costs across the 
population any longterm care proposal keyed to private insurance 
is going to be a failed policy he said 
the fact is that grandma cant afford longterm care 
insurance pollack said private insurance that claims to 
protect older americans from the high cost of nursing homes is 
itself so expensive that only the very richest elderly can afford 
the premiums 
don white a spokesman for the health insurance association of 
america said the organization hopes to see a publicprivate 
solution to the longterm care problem with private insurers 
playing a far larger role than that envisioned by families usa 
about 40 percent of elderly people can afford to buy private 
longterm care insurance according to hiaa 
its clear that the government cant do the job by itself the 
private companies cant do the job by themselves weve got to do 
it together white said its the role of the government to 
provide for those who are poor or near poor those who need 
government assistance 
with the costs of nursing home care averaging more than 2000 a 
month older americans and their families have been voicing 
increasing concern about the need for protection against such 
staggering costs 
private longterm care insurance was virtually nonexistent 
before 1980 but the market has grown rapidly in recent years with 
more than 100 companies now offering policies and more than 13 
million policies having been sold by mid1989 
families usa studied the average cost of basic policies issued 
by nine leading insurance companies and found that annual premiums 
averaged 1255 when purchased at age 65 at age 79 premiums 
averaged 3860 
policies were considered unaffordable when annual premiums 
pushed total health care costs to more than 10 percent of a 
persons yearly income and annuitized assets 
the fact is that nursing home insurance is well beyond the 
reach of most elderly couples and the situation is even tougher for 
widows or widowers who are most in need of longterm care 
pollack said some older people who fear the high costs of nursing 
home care purchase insurance that is far beyond their means and 
forego meals and medicine to pay for it he said 
pollack said public opinion surveys indicate most americans 
would be willing to pay extra taxes for longterm care protection 
he said possible financing mechanisms could include added payroll 
taxes or changes in the gift and estate tax 
the foundation said it was sending copies of its report to the 
pepper commission made up of members of congress and white house 
appointees which is trying to come up with a solution to the 
longterm care problem 
the commission estimates 9 million americans currently need 
longterm care with the numbers expected to grow as the population 
ages 
