<TEXT>
the bush administration said monday it will 
move to end controls on overseas sales of computers and other 
technology readily available to the public 
the policy overhaul will have an immediate effect on much of 
eastern europe but no immediate effect on the soviet union 
meanwhile sevral us officials have opened talks in london to 
prepare for joint steps by 17 nations to accelerate delivery of 
advanced technology to such countries as poland hungary and 
czechoslovakia 
the political and military environment is changing the 
situation is different today than it was a year ago white house 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said 
for more than 40 years the united states and its allies have 
imposed stiff curbs on technology sales to communist countries on 
security grounds but the advent of mikhail s gorbachev as leader 
of the soviet union in 1985 and the spread of reform in the eastern 
bloc spured many western governments to push for an easing of 
restrictions 
at a national security council meeting on friday the bush 
administration decided to take a softer approach as well sources 
said two parallel decisions were made to work out a joint 
agreement at a meeting in paris next month to provide advanced 
technology to eastern europe and to conduct a comprehensive review 
of us policy 
officials of the state department the pentagon and the commerce 
department participated in the decision state and commerce were 
more willing to permit the technology transfers than the defense 
department 
the state department spokeswoman margaret d tutwiler said the 
underlining us principles were 
support for reform in eastern europe 
strengthening protection for truly strategic goods and 
technologies 
more rapid modernization of the current lists of controlled 
items 
decontrol of offtheshelf commodities readily availble to the 
general public 
she said the administration wanted to take advantage of a 
changing enviornment in eastern europe in the soviet union 
she said the situation has not evolved to the same extent 
fitzwater called the steps being taken a prudent change 
that will not jeopardize strategic interests 
a group of us officials led by allan wendt of the state 
departments office of strategic technology policy flew to london 
over the weekend to meet with british officials 
the officials will go on to the netherlands west germany and 
italy meanwhile delegations from canada and japan will come to 
washington for talks this week and french and danish experts are 
due here next week 
the discussions are in preparation for a meeting in paris in 
midfebruary of cocom the coordination committee for multilateral 
export control there the united states hopes to work out details 
of what kind of equipment will be cleared for eastern europe and 
how much of it 
cocom which includes all 16 nato countries except iceland plus 
japan and australia attempts to coordinate western deliveries of 
technology to eastern european countries the united states has 
been among the most reluctant to provide high technology to allies 
of the soviet union 
the countries likely to be assisted include poland hungary and 
czechoslovakia all of which have shed communist domination nd are 
adopting capitalistic approaches to their weak economies 
the meeting in paris is designed to adopt uniform rules to guide 
technology transfers in this respect the administrations 
decision to liberalize restrictions could be balanced against the 
more eager approaches of some other cocom members and produce a 
compromise 
the net result however would be to deliver better computers 
and telecommunications equipment to members of the eastern bloc 
provided semisensitive technology is not then turned over to the 
soviet union 
