<TEXT>
czechoslovakia has asked to join the 
international monetary fund a major source of loans to countries 
in financial trouble the fund announced monday 
china poland hungary and yugoslavia are already members 
soviet leaders have said they would like to join the 152 countries 
that make up the organization the us government which holds the 
biggest single block of votes has said it does not consider the 
soviets ready 
the us central intelligence agency estimated czechoslovakias 
debt in 1988 at 61 billion much less than polands 385 billion 
and less than that of most other eastern european countries one 
exception is romania which under the late president nicolae 
ceausescu paid off virtually all its foreign debt 
the funds announcement recalled that czechoslovakia was one of 
the original members when the fund was organized just after world 
war ii but withdrew in 1954 after the communists took over the 
government no difficulty is expected in winning membership 
approval for czechoslovakia to rejoin 
the country probably will need financial help as it shifts from 
state control of the economy to something closer to a market 
system the imf specializes in shortterm loans for countries with 
payments difficulties 
membership in the fund also opens the way to membership in its 
sister organization the world bank also based in washington the 
bank is the largest source of longterm development loans to the 
third world 
a loan from the imf can open the way to borrowing from other 
lenders including individual governments and private banks the 
fund has negotiated a 710 million loan to poland and approval by 
the member governments is expected soon 
the application of czechoslovakia and the prospect that east 
germany romania and bulgaria may follow come as the fund is 
seeking a major increase in its resources now equivalent to about 
117 billion 
michel camdessus the funds french managing director has asked 
for a doubling of quotas as contributions are called and most 
member countrties went along but the united states britain and 
saudi arabia all influential members have argued for a smaller 
increase 
</TEXT>
