<TEXT>
us legal obstacles to trade with the soviet 
union will be gone by june the president of the governments 
exportimport bank predicted monday 
its important because our competitors have about 12 billion 
worth of trade business with the soviets joseph d macomber told 
the bankers association for foreign trade weve got a lot of 
catching up to do 
macomber predicted that the obstacles will be abolished before 
president bush meets the heads of other major industrialized 
nations for their annual summit this year in houston 
the exportimport bank which lends to purchasers in foreign 
countries at subsidized rates to promote the sale of american 
industrial products is barred by law from lending to the soviet 
union 
the bush administration has been waiting until the supreme 
soviet passes a new law on emigration before it moves to lift the 
restrictions imposed by the 1975 jacksonvanik amendment the 
object of the amendment was to encourage freer movement of jews out 
of the soviet union 
another legal provision the stevenson amendment sets a limit 
of 300 million on what the bank can lend or guarantee in loans to 
the soviets macomber quoted one of his analysts as saying 
that ought to get us through the first 30 days 
a third restriction the byrd amendment puts a limit of 40 
million on what can be lent to help finance soviet energy 
production 
